{"title_page": "Death of JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey", "text_new": "{{short description|death of American child beauty queen}}{{Redirect|JonBen\u00e9t|the American noise rock outfit from Houston, Texas|The Jonben\u00e9t}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               =  JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey\n| image              =  Jonbenet-ramsey.jpg\n| image_upright =\n| image_size = <!-- DISCOURAGED per WP:IMGSIZE. Use image_upright. -->\n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = JonBen\u00e9t Patricia Ramsey\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1990|08|06|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place        = [[Atlanta|Atlanta, Georgia]], U.S.\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|1996|12|25|1990|08|06}}\n| death_place        = [[Boulder, Colorado]], U.S.\n| death_cause        = [[Asphyxia]] by strangulation<br />Craniocerebral trauma\n| resting_place      = [[St. James Episcopal Cemetery]]<br />[[Marietta, Georgia]], U.S.\n| resting_place_coordinates =  {{coord|33.95501|-84.55637}}\n| parents             = [[John Bennett Ramsey|John Ramsey]]<br />[[Patsy Ramsey]]\n}}\n\n'''JonBen\u00e9t Patricia Ramsey''' (August 6, 1990 \u2013 December 25, 1996) was an [[Americans|American]] [[child beauty pageant|child beauty queen]] who was killed at the age of 6 in her family's home in [[Boulder, Colorado]]. A lengthy handwritten [[ransom]] note was found in the house. Her father [[John Bennett Ramsey|John]] found the girl's body in the basement of their house about eight hours after she had been reported [[missing person|missing]]. She sustained a broken skull from a blow to the head and had been strangled; a [[garrote]] was found tied around her neck. The [[autopsy]] report stated that the official cause of death was \"[[asphyxia]] by [[Strangling|strangulation]] associated with [[Traumatic brain injury|craniocerebral trauma]].\"<ref name=\"Klaver\">{{cite book |last= Klaver| first= Elizabeth |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tUgF9udmFuEC&pg=PA2|title=Sites of Autopsy in Contemporary Culture|year=2012|publisher=SUNY Press| isbn=0-791-48342-8 |page=2}}</ref><ref name=AutopsyReport/> Her death was ruled a [[homicide]].<ref name=\"Chan\"/> The case generated nationwide public and media interest, in part because her mother [[Patsy Ramsey]] (herself a former beauty queen) had entered JonBen\u00e9t into a series of [[child beauty pageant]]s. The crime is still unsolved and remains an open investigation with the Boulder Police Department.\n\nThe police initially suspected that the ransom note had been written by JonBen\u00e9t's mother, and that the note and appearance of the child's body had been staged by her parents in order to cover up the crime. However, in 1998, the [[District Attorney]] (DA) said that due to a new [[DNA]] analysis, none of the immediate family members were under suspicion for the crime.<ref name=\"9news.com\">{{cite web|first=Mary T. |last=Lacy |date=July 9, 2008 |title=Twentieth Judicial District, District Attorney's Office, Letter to John Ramsey |url=http://www.9news.com/pdfs/ramseyDA.pdf |archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20081218174842/http://www.9news.com/pdfs/ramseyDA.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=December 18, 2008|publisher=[[KUSA (TV)|KUSA 9 News]] |location=Denver, Colorado |format=PDF |access-date=September 5, 2015 }}</ref> Also in 1998, the police and the DA both said that JonBen\u00e9t's brother Burke, who was nine years old at the time of her death, was not a suspect.<ref name=\"DC Not Burke\" /><ref name=\"DC Burke gj\" /> The Ramseys gave several televised interviews but resisted police questioning except on their own terms. In October 2013, unsealed court documents revealed that a 1999 [[grand jury]] had recommended filing charges against JonBen\u00e9t's parents for permitting the child to be in a threatening situation. John and Patsy were also accused of hindering the [[prosecution]] of an unidentified person who had \"committed ... the crime of [[first-degree murder|murder in the first degree]] and [[child abuse]] resulting in death\".<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/10/25/justice/jonbenet-ramsey-documents/index.html|title=Papers: Grand jury in 1999 sought to indict JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey's parents|first1=Michael|last1=Martinez|first2=Faith|last2=Karimi|publisher=CNN|date=October 25, 2013}}</ref> However, the DA determined that there was insufficient evidence to pursue a successful [[indictment]].<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nIn 2002, the DA's successor took over investigation of the case from the police and primarily pursued the theory that an intruder had committed the killing. In 2003, trace DNA that was taken from the victim's clothes was found to belong to an unknown male; each of the family's DNA had been excluded from this match. The DA sent the Ramseys a letter of apology in 2008, declaring the family \"completely cleared\" by the DNA results.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/video/playerIndex?id=5349856 |title=JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey's Parents Cleared |publisher=[[ABC News]] |date=July 10, 2008 |access-date=September 5, 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130609061202/http://abcnews.go.com/video/playerIndex?id=5349856 |archivedate=June 9, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Others, including former Boulder police chief Mark Beckner, disagreed with exonerating the Ramseys, criticizing exonerating anyone based on a small piece of evidence that has not yet been proven to be connected.<ref name=\"Time Inc.\">{{cite book|authors =The Editors of People|title =PEOPLE True Crimes: Cases That Shocked America|isbn =1683305167 |publisher=[[Time Inc. Books]]|year=2016|pages=9\u201311|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=heSiDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA9&lpg=PA9}}</ref><ref name=\"NYP Morabito\">{{cite news | url=https://nypost.com/2016/09/12/jonbenet-ramsey-series-questions-key-dna-evidence/ | title=JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey series questions key DNA evidence | author=Andrea Morabito | date=September 12, 2016  | access-date=September 28, 2016 | newspaper=New York Post }}</ref> In February 2009, the Boulder police took the case back from the DA and reopened the investigation.<ref name= bonus>{{cite news |first=Vanessa |last=Miller |date=February 2, 2009 |url=http://www.coloradodaily.com/ci_13112748 |title=Boulder police take back Ramsey case |work=[[Colorado Daily]] |access-date=September 5, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923205547/http://www.coloradodaily.com/ci_13112748 |archive-date=September 23, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nMedia coverage of the case has focused on JonBen\u00e9t's brief beauty pageant career, as well as her parents' wealth and the unusual evidence found in the case. Media reports questioned how the police handled the case. Ramsey family members and their friends have filed [[defamation]] suits against several media organizations.\n\n==Life and interment==\n[[File:JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey grave.jpg|right|220px|thumb|JonBen\u00e9t's grave at Saint James Episcopal Cemetery in Marietta, Georgia.]]\nJonBen\u00e9t Ramsey was born in 1990 in [[Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], the younger of two children of Patricia (1956\u20132006)<ref>{{cite news |last1=Reed |first1=Christopher |title=Obituary: Patsy Ramsey |url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2006/jun/27/guardianobituaries.usa |access-date=September 15, 2018 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=June 28, 2006}}</ref> and John Ramsey (1943\u2013). She had an older brother named Burke (1987\u2013).<ref name=\"People1997\">{{cite journal |last= Jerome| first= Richard| date= October 6, 1997| title= Mystery Couple|url=http://people.com/archive/cover-story-mystery-couple-vol-48-no-14/|journal=People|publisher=Time Inc.| volume= 48|issue=14|issn=0093-7673}}</ref> Her first name combines her father's first and middle names, and her mother's first name was used as her middle name. JonBen\u00e9t was enrolled in [[kindergarten]] at [[Boulder Valley School District|High Peaks Elementary School]] in [[Boulder, Colorado|Boulder]], [[Colorado]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Schiller|first=Lawrence |title=Perfect Murder, Perfect Town|url=https://archive.org/details/perfectmurderper00schi|url-access=registration|year=1999|publisher=HarperCollins|isbn=0-060-19153-8|page=[https://archive.org/details/perfectmurderper00schi/page/38 38]}}</ref>\n\nJonBen\u00e9t's body was found on December 26, 1996 in her family home in Boulder, Colorado. She was buried at [[St. James Episcopal Cemetery]] in [[Marietta, Georgia]]. She was interred next to her much older half-sister Elizabeth Pasch Ramsey, who had died in a car crash four years earlier at age 22.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Williams|first=Paige|date=October 2006|title=Grave Faith|journal=Atlanta Magazine|publisher=Emmis Communications|volume=46|issue=6|pages=84, 87|issn=0004-6701|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rQ8AAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA82}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1997-02-21/news/9702210074_1_jonbenet-ramsey-ramsey-investigation-boulder-police |title= Reports Sought In Jonbenet's Sister's Death|last=McSherry Breslin| first= Meg|date=February 21, 1997 |website=ChicagoTribune.com |access-date= November 19, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Parents==\n[[John Bennett Ramsey|John Ramsey]] was a businessman who was the president of Access Graphics, a computer system company that later became a subsidiary of [[Lockheed Martin]].<ref name= hewitt>{{cite journal |last=Hewitt|first=Bill|date=January 20, 1997|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20143261,00.html |title= Lost Innocent|journal=People|publisher=Time Inc.| volume= 47| issue=2| issn=0093-7673}}</ref> His first marriage ended in [[divorce]] in 1978. His two surviving adult children (a son and a daughter) lived elsewhere. His 22-year-old daughter from the first marriage, Elizabeth, died in a 1992 car crash.<ref name=\"NW No Justice\"/>\n\nIn 1991, John had moved with his second wife and family to Boulder, where Access Graphics' headquarters was located.<ref name=inside>{{cite book |last1= Thomas| first1=Steve |last2=Davis|first2=Donald A.|title=JonBenet: Inside the Ramsey Murder Investigation| year= 2011| publisher= Macmillan|isbn=9781429981736}}</ref>\n \nPatricia \"Patsy\" Ramsey entered their daughter in various [[child beauty pageant]]s that were held in Boulder.<ref name= hewitt /> JonBen\u00e9t won the titles of America's Royale Miss, Little Miss Charlevoix, Little Miss Colorado, Colorado State All-Star Kids Cover Girl, and National Tiny Miss Beauty.<ref name=fast-facts>{{cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/08/29/us/jonbenet-ramsey-murder-fast-facts/|title=JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey Murder Fast Facts|date=October 28, 2014|website=Cnn.com|access-date=November 19, 2014}}</ref> JonBen\u00e9t's active role in child beauty pageants and Patsy's reported \"[[stage mother|pageant mother]]\" behavior were reported by the media after the murder.<ref name=\"People1997\"/>\n\nIn the summer of 1997\u2014approximately six months after JonBen\u00e9t's death\u2014the Ramseys moved to a new home in Atlanta after a summer at their vacation retreat in [[Charlevoix, Michigan]].<ref name=\"HP Timeline\" /> Patsy died of [[ovarian cancer]] at age 49 in 2006; she was interred next to her daughter.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.cnn.com/2006-06-24/justice/ramsey.death_1_jonbenet-ovarian-cancer-john-ramsey?_s=PM:LAW |work=CNN |title=Patsy Ramsey, JonBenet's mother, dies |date=June 24, 2006 |access-date=September 14, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151001012629/http://www.cnn.com/2006/LAW/06/24/ramsey.death/index.html?_s=PM%3ALAW |archivedate=October 1, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Evidence==\n===Ransom note===\n[[File:JonBenet Ramsey ransom note.jpg|thumb|The ransom note]]<!--\n{{Quote box |width=30em |bgcolor=#c6dbf7 |align=right |title= Text of the ransom note |quote=Mr. Ramsey,<br /><br />Listen carefully! We are a group of individuals that represent a small foreign faction. We <s>do</s> respect your {{sic|bus|siness}} but not the country that it serves. At this time we have your daughter in our {{sic|po|session}}. She is safe and unharmed and if you want her to see 1997, you must follow our instructions to the letter.<br /><br />You will withdraw $118,000.00 from your account. $100,000 will be in $100 bills and the remaining $18,000 in $20 bills. Make sure that you bring an adequate size attache to the bank. When you get home you will put the money in a brown paper bag. I will call you between 8 and 10 am tomorrow to instruct you on delivery. The delivery will be exhausting so I advise you to be rested. If we monitor you getting the money early, we might call you early to arrange an earlier delivery of the money and hence a {{sic}} earlier <s>delivery</s> pick-up of your daughter.<br /><br />Any deviation of my instructions will result in the immediate execution of your daughter. You will also be denied her remains for proper burial. The two gentlemen watching over your daughter do <sup>not</sup> particularly like you so I advise you not to provoke them. Speaking to anyone about your situation, such as Police, F.B.I., etc., will result in your daughter being beheaded. If we catch you talking to a stray dog, she dies. If you alert bank authorities, she dies. If the money is in any way marked or tampered with, she dies. You will be scanned for electronic devices and if any are found, she dies. You can try to deceive us but be warned that we are familiar with law enforcement countermeasures and tactics. You stand a 99% chance of killing your daughter if you try to out smart {{sic}} us. Follow our instructions and you stand a 100% chance of getting her back.<br /><br />You and your family are under constant scrutiny as well as the authorities. Don't try to grow a brain John. You are not the only fat cat around so don't think that killing will be difficult. Don't underestimate us John. Use that good southern common sense of yours. It is up to you now John!<br /><br />Victory!<br /><br />S.B.T.C|source=[https://web.archive.org/web/20061208031500/http://www.thedenverchannel.com/2006/0818/9699449.jpg Original text]}}-->\n\nAccording to statements that Patsy gave to authorities on December 26, 1996, she realized that her daughter was [[missing person|missing]] after she found a two-and-a-half-page handwritten [[ransom]] note on the kitchen staircase. The note demanded {{US$|118000|1996}}.<ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/US/9701/21/ramsey.update/index.html |title=Police drop some potential suspects in Ramsey killing|website=CNN.com |date=January 21, 1997 |access-date=June 22, 2011}}</ref> John pointed out to police first on the scene that the amount was nearly identical to his Christmas bonus of the prior year, which suggested that someone who would have access to that information would be involved in the crime. Investigators looked at several theories behind the dollar amount demanded. They considered employees at Access Graphics who may have known of the amount of John's prior bonus. They also considered the possibility that the ransom demand was a reference to [[Psalm 118]], and spoke to religious sources to determine possible relevance.<ref>Schiller, Lawrence (1999). ''Perfect Murder, Perfect Town'', p. 323, p. 447.  HarperCollins, New York. {{ISBN|0-06-109696-2}}</ref>\n\nThe ransom note was unusually long. The [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] told the police that it was very unusual for such a note to be written at the crime scene.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://fox2now.com/2015/02/26/jonbenet-ramsey-case-10-things-the-ex-police-chief-just-revealed/ | title=JonBenet Ramsey case: 9 things the ex-police chief just revealed | author=CNN Wires | publisher=Fox2News | date=February 26, 2015 | access-date=October 2, 2016 }}</ref> The police believed that the note was staged, because it did not have any fingerprints except for Patsy's and authorities who had handled it,<ref name=\"Time Inc.\"/> and because it included an unusual use of exclamation marks and initialisms.<ref name=\"Expers dissect\">{{cite news | url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/video/9271998-experts-dissect-jonbenet-ramsey-ransom-note-29249678 | title=Experts Dissect JonBenet Ramsey Ransom Note | date=September 27, 1998 | publisher=ABC News | access-date=October 2, 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.thedenverchannel.com/news/front-range/boulder/jonbenet-ramsey-case-former-boulder-police-chief-mark-beckner-says-police-botched-initial-handling | title=JonBenet Ramsey case: Former Boulder police chief Mark Beckner says police botched initial handling | author=Associated Press, Deb Stanley | publisher=The Denver Channel, local ABC station | date=February 25, 2015 | access-date=October 2, 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201080750/http://www.thedenverchannel.com/news/front-range/boulder/jonbenet-ramsey-case-former-boulder-police-chief-mark-beckner-says-police-botched-initial-handling | archive-date=December 1, 2017 | url-status=dead }}</ref> The note and a practice draft were written with a pen and pad of paper from the Ramsey home.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/12/05/us/bungled-jonbenet-case-bursts-a-city-s-majesty.html|title=Bungled JonBen\u00e9t Case Bursts a City's Majesty|date=December 5, 1997| work= [[The New York Times]] |access-date= September 13, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.nytimes.com/1997/01/09/us/report-tells-of-draft-note-for-ransom.html|title=Report Tells Of Draft Note For Ransom|date=January 9, 1997|work= The New York Times |accessdate= September 13, 2016}}</ref> According to a [[Colorado Bureau of Investigation]] report, \"There are indications that the author of the ransom note is Patricia Ramsey.\" However, the evidence fell short of a definitive conclusion.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=875&dat=19970904&id=SdQLAAAAIBAJ&sjid=M1YDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6638,205639|title=Patricia Ramsey's handwriting 'set off bells'|date=September 4, 1997| work= Today's News-Herald| publisher=Google News Archive Search|page=5|access-date=December 23, 2010|location=Denver}}</ref> Michael Baden, a board-certified [[forensic pathology|forensic pathologist]], who had consulted with both sides of the case, said he had never seen a note like it in his 60-year experience, and that he did not think it was written by an outside stranger.<ref name=\"Time Inc.\"/>\n\nA federal court ruled it highly unlikely that Patsy wrote the note, citing six certified handwriting experts. The court bemoaned the existence of self-proclaimed experts \u2013 without credentials \u2013 trying to wrangle their way into the case by accusing Patsy without scientific basis.<ref>https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/district-courts/FSupp2/253/1323/2567726/</ref>\n\n===9-1-1 call and initial search for the child===\nThe only people known to be in the house on the night of JonBen\u00e9t's death were her immediate family: Patsy and John Ramsey and their son Burke.<ref>{{cite magazine | url=http://www.people.com/article/jonbenet-ramsey-case-5-things-to-know | title=JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey Case: 5 Things to Know About the 19-Year-Old Mystery | magazine=People | date=August 2, 2016 | author=Char Adams | access-date=September 30, 2016 }}</ref> The ransom note contained specific instructions against contacting police and friends, but Patsy telephoned the police at 5:52&nbsp;a.m. [[Mountain Time Zone|MST]].<ref name=\"DC Tragic case\">{{cite news | url=http://www.dailycamera.com/ci_22446420/jonbenet-ramsey-case-history-grand-jury | title=JonBenet Ramsey's death a tragic, bizarre case from the start | author=Charlie Brennan | newspaper=Daily Camera | date=January 27, 2013 | access-date=September 29, 2016 }}</ref> She also called family and friends.<ref name=\"Maloney\">{{cite web| url= http://www.crimemagazine.com/murder-jonben%C3%A9t-ramsey| title= The Murder of JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey| last1= Maloney| first1= J. J.| last2= O'Connor| first2= J. Patrick| date= May 7, 1999| website=Crimemagazine.com| accessdate= November 19, 2014| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141129041656/http://www.crimemagazine.com/murder-jonben%C3%A9t-ramsey| archive-date= November 29, 2014| url-status= dead| df= mdy-all}}</ref> Two police officers responded to the [[9-1-1]] call and arrived at the Ramsey home within three minutes. They conducted a cursory search of the house but did not find any sign of forced entry.<ref name=\"Maloney\" />{{efn|It was later determined that some windows and a door had been left unlocked that night. In addition, a basement window was previously broken by John Ramsey when he was locked out of the house.<ref name=\"Newsweek 2016\" />\n\n[[Lou Smit]], a retired and successful homicide detective, was brought in to investigate the case. He quickly became a proponent of the intruder theory, and believed that the intruder entered through this basement window. A suitcase was found on the floor almost directly underneath this window. Smit theorized the attacker(s) planned to use this suitcase either to take JonBen\u00e9t alive as a kidnap victim or move her body out of the house, but this proved impossible.<ref name=\"DC Smit theory\">{{cite news | url=http://web.dailycamera.com/extra/ramsey/2001/01lrams.html | title=Smit presents intruder theory | author=Christopher Anderson | newspaper=Daily Camera | date=May 1, 2001 | access-date=September 29, 2016 }}</ref>}}\n\nOfficer Rick French went to the basement and came to a door that was secured by a wooden latch. He paused for a moment in front of the door, but made a critical error when he walked away without opening it. French later explained that he was looking for an exit route used by the kidnapper, which the closed inside peg ruled out. Unbeknownst to him, JonBen\u00e9t's body was on the other side of the door.<ref name=\"Newsweek 2016\">{{cite magazine | url=http://www.newsweek.com/jonbenet-ramsey-door-cops-never-opened-501705 | title=JonBen\u00e9t': The door the cops never opened | magazine=Newsweek | date=September 23, 2016 | access-date=September 28, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nJohn made arrangements to pay the ransom. A [[forensic]]s team was dispatched to the house. The team initially believed that the child had been [[kidnapping|kidnapped]], and JonBen\u00e9t's bedroom was the only room in the house that was cordoned off to prevent contamination of evidence. No precautions were taken to prevent [[Contaminated evidence|contamination of evidence]] in the rest of the house.<ref name=\"Newsweek 2016\" /> Meanwhile, friends and the family's minister arrived at the home to support the Ramseys. Victim advocates also arrived at the scene. Visitors picked up and cleaned surfaces in the kitchen, possibly destroying evidence.<ref name=\"Newsweek 2016\" /> Boulder detective Linda Arndt arrived at about 8 a.m. MST, with the goal of awaiting the kidnapper(s)' instructions, but there was never an attempt by anyone to claim the money.<ref name=Oliva />\n\n===Discovery of the body===\nAt 1:00&nbsp;p.m. MST, Detective Arndt asked John Ramsey and Fleet White, a family friend, to search the house to see if \"anything seemed amiss.\"<ref name=\"Newsweek 2016\" /> They started their search in the basement. John opened the latched door which Officer French had overlooked and found his daughter's body in one of the rooms.<ref name=\"Newsweek 2016\" /> JonBen\u00e9t's mouth was covered with [[duct tape]], a [[nylon]] cord was found around her wrists and neck, and her torso was covered by a white blanket.<ref name=\"RS\" /><ref name=Douglas /> John Ramsey picked up the child's body and took it upstairs. When JonBen\u00e9t was moved, the crime scene was further contaminated, and critical forensic evidence was disturbed for the returning forensics team.<ref name=\"Newsweek 2016\"/>{{efn|Former FBI profiler [[John E. Douglas]], who was brought in to assist the Ramseys' lawyers on the case in January 1997 to assess whether the Ramseys were involved, stated that if a family member was involved in a murder, they would generally construe events so that another person found the body. In this case, John found the body and his friend followed him into the basement room. According to Douglas, when a family member is involved in a murder, they are likely to cover their child's body in a protective manner, covering all but their head. In this case, just the torso was covered, which did not denote the kind of act a parent would generally perform. In addition, John removed the duct tape from her mouth and loosened the cord around her, which goes against the theory of \"staging\" the body. Arndt made an error when she moved JonBen\u00e9t into the living room.<ref name=Douglas>{{cite book | chapter = The JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey Murder | title=The Cases That Haunt Us: From Jack the Ripper to Jon Benet Ramsey, The FBI's Legendary Mindhunter Sheds New Light on the Mysteries That Won't Go Away | author= [[John E. Douglas]]  and Mark Olshaker | publisher=Scribner | year=2001 | isbn=0671017063  }}</ref>}}\n\nEach of the Ramseys provided handwriting, blood, and hair samples to the police. John and Patsy participated in a preliminary interview for more than two hours, and Burke was also interviewed within the first couple of weeks following JonBen\u00e9t's death.<ref name=Douglas />\n\n===Autopsy===\nThe [[autopsy]] revealed that JonBen\u00e9t had been killed by [[strangulation]] and a [[skull fracture]]. The official cause of death was \"[[asphyxia]] by strangulation associated with craniocerebral trauma.\"<ref name=\"Klaver\"/><ref name=AutopsyReport>{{cite web | url=http://hosted.ap.org/specials/interactives/_national/jonbenet_ramsey/jonbenet_ramsey_autopsy.pdf | title=Autopsy Report | date=December 27, 1996 | publisher=Office of the Boulder County Coroner | access-date=September 29, 2016 }}</ref> There was no evidence of conventional [[rape]], although [[sexual assault]] could not be ruled out. Although no [[semen]] was found, there was evidence that there had been a vaginal injury. At the time of the autopsy, the pathologist recorded that it appeared her vaginal area had been wiped with a cloth.<ref name=\"DP Evidence\">{{cite news | url=http://extras.denverpost.com/news/ram1014k.htm | title=No indictment: Evidence voluminous but tricky | author=Karen Aug\u00e9|newspaper=[[Denver Post]] | date=October 14, 1999 | access-date=September 28, 2016 }}</ref> Her death was ruled a [[homicide]].<ref name=\"Chan\">{{cite news|last=Chan|first=Melissa|title=JonBenet Ramsey: What to Know About the Beauty Queen's Murder 20 Years Later|date=September 12, 2016|access-date=September 29, 2016|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|url=http://time.com/4478185/jonbenet-ramsey-murder-20-years/}}</ref>\n\nA [[garrote]] that was made from a length of nylon cord and the broken handle of a paintbrush was tied around JonBen\u00e9t's neck and had apparently been used to strangle her. Part of the bristle end of the paintbrush was found in a tub containing Patsy's art supplies, but the bottom third of it was never found despite extensive searching of the house by the police in subsequent days.<ref name= courttv>{{cite web |url= http://www.courttv.com/onair/shows/specials/jonbenet_anatomy_of_a_cold_case.html | title= JonBen\u00e9t: Anatomy of a Cold Case |publisher=Court TV |date=  | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060709195643/http://www.courttv.com/onair/shows/specials/jonbenet_anatomy_of_a_cold_case.html | archivedate=July 9, 2006}}</ref>\n\nThe autopsy revealed a \"vegetable or fruit material which may represent [[pineapple]],\" which JonBen\u00e9t had eaten a few hours before her death.<ref name=AutopsyReport/><ref name=hickey>{{citation |editor-last= Hickey| editor-first= Eric| title= Encyclopedia of Murder and Violent Crime| edition= illustrated, reprint| publisher= SAGE| year= 2003| isbn= 9780761924371}}</ref> Photographs of the home taken on the day when JonBen\u00e9t's body was found show a bowl of pineapple on the kitchen table with a spoon in it.<ref name=hickey/> However, neither John nor Patsy said they remembered putting the bowl on the table or feeding pineapple to JonBen\u00e9t.<ref name=hickey/><ref name=interrogation/> Police reported that they found JonBen\u00e9t's nine-year-old brother Burke Ramsey's fingerprints on the bowl.<ref name=interrogation>{{cite news |title = Searching: The Interrogation Tapes|url = http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2002/10/01/48hours/main523875.shtml|publisher = 48 Hours (CBS News)|date=October 1, 2002|accessdate = July 11, 2008}}</ref> The Ramseys have always said that Burke slept through the entire night until he was awakened several hours after the police arrived.<ref name= inside />{{rp|w186\u201387}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://extras.denverpost.com/news/jon0526.htm|title=Victim's brother, 12, questioned|last=Robinson|first=Marilyn|date=May 26, 1997| work= DenverPost.com|access-date=November 19, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Blood samples===\nIn December 2003, forensic investigators extracted enough material from a mixed blood sample found on JonBen\u00e9t's underwear to establish a [[DNA]] profile.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2004/12/16/48hours/main661569.shtml |work=CBS News |title=JonBenet: DNA Rules Out Parents |date=December 16, 2004}}</ref> That DNA belonged to an unknown male person, and excluded the DNA of each of the Ramseys. The DNA was submitted to the FBI's [[Combined DNA Index System]] (CODIS), a database containing more than 1.6 million DNA profiles, but the sample did not match any profile in the database.<ref name=\"DC Brennan\" /> In October 2016, a report said that new forensic analysis with more sensitive techniques revealed that the original DNA contained genetic markers from two individuals other than JonBen\u00e9t.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-crime-jonbenet-idUSKCN12T007 |work=Reuters |title=DNA cited to clear JonBenet Ramsey family in murder in question: report |date=October 28, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailycamera.com/news/jonbenet-ramsey/ci_30514220/jonbenet-ramsey-dna-evidence |work=Daily Camera |title=DNA in doubt: New analysis challenges DA's exoneration of Ramseys |date=October 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\nA. James Kolar, who was a lead investigator for the D.A.'s office, said that there were additional traces of male DNA found on the cord and paintbrush that Boulder district attorney Mary Lacy did not mention, and that there were six separate DNA samples belonging to unknown individuals that were found by the test.<ref name=\"Time Inc.\"/> Former FBI profiler Candice Delong believes that the DNA, having shown up identically in several different places on multiple surfaces, belongs to the killer.<ref>https://www.denverpost.com/2016/09/19/burke-ramsey-hopes-jonbenet-murder-investigation-finds-killer/</ref> Former Adams County, Colorado, District Attorney Bob Grant, who has assisted the Boulder DA's office on the case for many years, also believes that the DNA evidence is significant, saying that any resolution of the case would have to explain how the DNA showed up on several pieces of JonBen\u00e9t's clothing.<ref>http://www.dailycamera.com/ci_30317043/boulder-police-chief-updates-jonbenet-ramsey-case-20</ref> Forensic pathologist Michael Baden said, \"Trace amounts of DNA can get on places and clothing from all different, nonsuspicious means. There is no forensic evidence to show that this is a stranger murder.\"<ref name=\"Time Inc.\"/>\n\n==Investigation==\nExperts, media commentators, and the Ramseys have identified potential suspects in the case.<ref name=\"CBS DNA Rules\" /> Boulder police initially focused almost exclusively upon John and Patsy,<ref name=\"CBS DNA Rules\" /> but by October 1997 had over 1,600 people in their index of [[person of interest|persons of interest]] for the case.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://web.dailycamera.com/extra/ramsey/1997/10/24-1.html | title=Police cast wide net in Ramsey investigation | author=Alli Krupski | newspaper=Daily Camera|date=October 24, 1997 | accessdate=October 1, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nErrors that were made in the initial investigation complicated the resolution of the investigation and applicable theory. Those errors included loss and contamination of evidence, lack of experienced and technical staff on the investigation, evidence shared with the Ramseys, and delayed informal interviews with the parents.<ref name=\"Newsweek 2016\" /><ref name=\"NYT Bungled\" />{{efn|A Boulder defense attorney, Lee Hill, commented that: \"The public feels that the police have coddled the Ramseys because they are rich and influential in Boulder.\"<ref name=\"NYT Bungled\" />}}\n\n[[Lou Smit]] was a detective who came out of retirement in early 1997 to assist the Boulder County [[District Attorney]]'s office with the case. In May 1998, he presented his findings to the Boulder police with other staff members of the DA's Office, concluding that the evidence pointed away from the Ramseys. They were unable to successfully challenge the police department's belief that the Ramseys were guilty. The DA's office sought to take control of the investigation.<ref name=\"KoJB\">{{cite AV media | title=The Killing of JonBen\u00e9t: The Truth Uncovered | publisher=Mills Productions for [[A&E (TV network)|A&E]] network| people=David Mills and Janet Taylor, executive producers for Mill Productions |medium=television | date=September 5, 2016 }}</ref> Due to the animosity between the police and the DA's office, and the pressure to obtain a conviction, [[Governor of Colorado|Colorado governor]] [[Roy Romer]] interceded and named Michael Kane as [[special prosecutor]] to initiate a [[grand jury]].<ref name=\"NW No Justice\">{{cite news | url=http://www.newsweek.com/no-justice-jonbenet-168028 | title=No Justice for JonBenet | work=[[Newsweek]] | date=October 24, 1999 | accessdate=September 30, 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://articles.philly.com/1998-08-11/news/25727328_1_special-prosecutor-roy-romer-district-attorney-alex-hunter | title=Special Prosecutor For Ramsey Case? Colorado's Governor Will Meet With Four Area District Attorneys To Decide Whether To Appoint One | date=August 11, 1998 | author=Gwen Florio | newspaper=The Philadelphia Inquirer | publisher=philly.com | access-date=September 30, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nTwo of the lead investigators in the case had opposing views. Both Lou Smit and Steve Thomas ultimately resigned {{ndash}} Smit because he believed that the investigation had incompetently overlooked the intruder hypothesis,<ref name=\"NW No Justice\" /> and Thomas because the DA's office had interfered with and failed to support the police investigation of the case.<ref name=\"Klaver\"/><ref name=inside/><ref name= courttv /><ref name=ThomasResignation>{{cite news |first=Steve |last=Thomas | url=http://web.dailycamera.com/extra/ramsey/1998/07thomle.html | title=The Thomas resignation letter | date=August 6, 1998| newspaper=Daily Camera }}</ref>\n\nA grand jury was convened beginning September 15, 1998 to consider [[indictment|indicting]] the Ramseys for charges relating to the case.<ref name=\"HP Timeline\">{{cite news | url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/01/28/jonbenet-ramsey-case-time_n_2561598.html | title=JonBenet Ramsey Case Timeline: 1996\u20132012 | date=January 27, 2013 |  author=<!-- Daily Camera staff --> | work=Huffington Post | accessdate=September 29, 2016 }}</ref><ref name=Garnett /> In 1999, the grand jury returned a [[true bill]] to charge the Ramseys with placing the child at risk in a way that led to her death and with [[obstruction of justice|obstructing an investigation of murder]], based on the [[probable cause]] standard applied in such grand jury proceedings. But [[Boulder County, Colorado|Boulder County]] District Attorney Alex Hunter did not prosecute them, because he did not believe that he could meet the higher standard of proving guilt [[beyond a reasonable doubt]] that is required for a criminal conviction.<ref name=Garnett />\n\nMary Lacy, the next Boulder County District Attorney, took over the investigation from the police on December 26, 2002. In April 2003, she agreed with a federal judge who sat on a 2002 [[libel]] case that evidence in the suit is \"more consistent with a theory that an intruder murdered JonBen\u00e9t than it was with a theory that Mrs. Ramsey did\".<ref name=\"HP Timeline\" /> On July 9, 2008, the Boulder District Attorney's office announced that, as a result of newly developed DNA sampling and testing techniques ([[touch DNA]] analysis), the Ramsey family members were excluded as suspects in the case. Lacy publicly exonerated the Ramseys.<ref name=ramseyspressrelease>{{cite news|title=Ramsey Press Release |last=Lacy |first=Mary T. |publisher=District Attorney's Office, Twentieth Judicial District, Boulder, Colorado |date=July 9, 2008 |url=http://www.bouldercounty.org/newsroom/templates/?a=1256&z=13 |access-date=July 9, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080801081500/http://www.bouldercounty.org/newsroom/templates/?a=1256&z=13 |archivedate=August 1, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/25608543/ns/us_news-crime_and_courts/t/family-cleared-jonbenet-ramseys-death/|title=Family cleared in JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey's death|date=July 9, 2008| website=NBCNews.com| access-date= November 19, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn February 2, 2009, Boulder police chief Mark Beckner announced that Stan Garnett, the new Boulder County District Attorney, was turning the case over to his agency, and that his team would resume investigating it.<ref name=bonus/> Garnett found that the [[statute of limitations]] for the crimes identified in the 1999 grand jury true bill had expired, and did not pursue review of the case against the Ramseys.<ref name=Garnett>{{cite web |last= Garnett| first= Stan| title= Boulder DA Stan Garnett: Another perspective on release of Ramsey indictment|url=http://www.dailycamera.com/guest-opinions/ci_24389428/stan-garnett-boulder-district-attorney-jonbenet-ramsey-case|website= Daily Camera}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2010, the Boulder police reopened the cold case. New interviews were conducted following a fresh inquiry by a committee that included state and federal investigators. Police were expected to use the latest [[DNA]] technology in their investigation.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/northamerica/usa/8044818/JonBenet-Ramsey-murder-case-reopened.html |location=London |work=The Daily Telegraph |first=Nick |last=Allen |title=JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey murder case reopened |date=October 5, 2010}}</ref> There was no new information gleaned from those interviews.<ref name=\"HP Kolar\">{{cite news | url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/07/18/jonbenet-ramsey-case-jame_n_1687905.html | title=JonBenet Ramsey Case: James Kolar, Former Leading Investigator Rejects Intruder Theory In New Book | date=July 20, 2012 | work=Huffington Post | access-date=September 30, 2016 }}</ref> It was reported in September 2016 that the investigation into JonBen\u00e9t's death continues to be an active homicide case, per Boulder Police Chief Greg Testa.<ref name=\"DC Brennan\">{{cite news | url=http://www.dailycamera.com/news/boulder/ci_30317043/boulder-police-chief-updates-jonbenet-ramsey-case-20 | title=Boulder police chief updates JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey case, 20 years on | author=Charlie Brennan | newspaper=[[Daily Camera]] | date=September 1, 2016 | access-date=September 26, 2016 }}</ref>{{efn|Boulder Police Chief Greg Testa stated in September 2016 that \"To date, the Boulder Police Department has processed more than 1,500 pieces of evidence, including the analysis of over 200 DNA samples. [...] Our major crimes unit has received and reviewed or investigated over 20,000 tips, letters or emails. Our detectives have traveled to over 18 states and interviewed or spoken with more than 1,000 individuals.\"<ref name=\"DC Brennan\" />}}\n\nIn 2015, Beckner disagreed with exonerating the Ramseys, stating, \"Exonerating anyone based on a small piece of evidence that has not yet been proved to even be connected to the crime is absurd.\"<ref name=\"Time Inc.\"/> He also stated that the unknown DNA from JonBenet's clothing \"has got to be the focus of the investigation\" at this point in time and that, until one can prove otherwise, \"the suspect is the donator [sic] of that unknown DNA.\"<ref>http://www.dailycamera.com/ci_27591666/mark-beckner-opens-up-about-jonbenet-ramsey-case</ref>  In 2016, Gordon Coombes, a former investigator for the Boulder County District Attorney's office, also questioned total absolution of the Ramseys, stating, \"We all shed DNA all the time within our skin cells. It can be deposited anywhere at any time for various reasons, reasons that are benign. To clear somebody just on the premise of touch DNA, especially when you have a situation where the crime scene wasn't secure at the beginning ... really is a stretch.\"<ref name=\"NYP Morabito\" /> Steven E. Pitt, a [[forensic psychiatrist]] hired by Boulder authorities, said, \"Lacy's public exoneration of the Ramseys was a big slap in the face to Chief Beckner and the core group of detectives who had been working on the case for years.\"<ref name=\"Time Inc.\"/>\n\n==Theories and suspects==\n===Family member theory===\nThere are two types of theories about the death of JonBen\u00e9t. One is the family member theory.<ref name=\"NYP Morabito\"/> Boulder police initially concentrated almost exclusively upon the parents, John and Patsy Ramsey.<ref name=\"CBS DNA Rules\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/jonbenet-dna-rules-out-parents/#comments |title=JonBenet: DNA Rules Out Parents |date=December 16, 2004 |website=CBSNews.com |accessdate=November 19, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160115025353/http://www.cbsnews.com/news/jonbenet-dna-rules-out-parents/ |archivedate=January 15, 2016 }}</ref><ref name=\"NYT Bungled\">{{ cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/12/05/us/bungled-jonbenet-case-bursts-a-city-s-majesty.html?_r=0 | title=Bungled JonBen\u00e9t Case Bursts a City's Majesty | author=James Brooke | date=December 5, 1997 | newspaper=The New York Times | access-date=September 28, 2016 }}</ref> According to [[Gregg McCrary]], a retired profiler with the FBI, \"statistically, it is a 12-to-1 probability that it's a family member or a care giver\" who is involved in the homicide of a child.<ref name=\"NYT Bungled\" />  The FBI has stated that there was a practiced note on the note pad that John Ramsey had given earlier that day and that the parents were involved. The police saw no evidence of a forced entry, but they did see evidence of staging of the scene, such as the ransom note. They did not find the Ramseys cooperative in helping them solve the death of their daughter.<ref name=\"NYT Bungled\" />{{efn|James Brooke of ''The New York Times'' reported, \n<blockquote>\"The Ramseys have consistently maintained their innocence. But for four months after the murder, they declined to talk to the police. Instead, they mounted a defense team that sounds like a defense lawyer's Christmas carol: eight lawyers, four publicists, three private investigators, two handwriting analysts and one retired F.B.I. profiler.\"<ref name=\"NYT Bungled\" />|name=Decline}} The Ramseys had said that their reluctance was due to their fear that there would not be a full investigation for intruders and that they would be hastily selected as the key suspects in the case, according to the ''Daily Camera''.<ref name=\"DC Tragic case\" />\n\nOne theory is that Patsy struck JonBen\u00e9t in a fit of rage after a bedwetting episode, and strangled her to cover up what had happened, after mistakenly thinking she was already dead.<ref name=\"DC Tragic case\"/><ref name=\"BC Dr Phil\" /> But Patsy did not have a known history of uncontrolled anger.<ref name=\"BC Dr Phil\" /> JonBen\u00e9t's brother later said, \"We didn't get spanked, nothing of the sort, nothing close, nothing near laying a finger on us, let alone killing your child.\"<ref name=\"BC Dr Phil\" />\n\nTheoretically, the strangulation could have been a \"[[red herring]]\" aspect to conceal other elements of the assault and killing.<ref name=\"KoJB\" /><ref name=\"BC Dr Phil\">{{cite news |url=http://www.dailycamera.com/news/boulder/ci_30359976/burke-ramsey-interview-dr-phil-jonbenet-boulder | title=Burke Ramsey responds to conspiracy theories, accusations about JonBen\u00e9t's murder | author=<!-- Denver Post staff --> | newspaper=Daily Camera | date=September 14, 2016 | access-date=September 26, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nBurke, who was nine years old at the time of JonBen\u00e9t's death, was interviewed by investigators at least three times.<ref name=\"DC Burke attny in town\" /> The first two interviews did not raise any concerns about him. A review by a child psychologist stated that it appeared that the Ramseys had \"healthy, caring family relationships\".<ref name=\"KoJB\" /> In 1998, Boulder Police Chief Mark Beckner said during an interview with a news reporter that Burke Ramsey was not involved in the killing of his sister. In May 1999, the Boulder County District Attorney's office reiterated that Burke Ramsey was not a suspect.<ref name=\"DC Not Burke\">{{cite news | url=http://web.dailycamera.com/extra/ramsey/1999/21arams.html | title=Burke Ramsey not suspect in killing, DA's office says | author=Christopher Anderson | newspaper=Daily Camera | date=May 1999 | access-date=October 1, 2016 }}</ref> The investigators had never considered him a suspect.<ref name=\"DC Burke gj\">{{cite news | url=http://web.dailycamera.com/extra/ramsey/1999/52699crams.html | title=Grand Jury heard from JonBen\u00e9t's brother| author=<!-- Camera staff and wire services -->|date=May 26, 1999 | access-date=October 1, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nThe Ramseys offered a $100,000 reward in a newspaper ad dated April 27, 1997.<ref name=\"HP Timeline\" /> Three days later, more than four months after the body of their daughter was found, they submitted for the first time to separate formal interviews at the Boulder County Justice Center.<ref name=\"HP Timeline\" />\n\nIn 1999, Colorado Governor [[Bill Owens (Colorado politician)|Bill Owens]] spoke out, telling the Ramsey couple to \"quit hiding behind their attorneys, quit hiding behind their [[public relations|PR]] firm\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/5260914.stm |title=Warning on JonBen\u00e9t speculation |work=BBC News |date=August 17, 2006 |access-date=June 22, 2011}}</ref>{{efn|name=Decline}}\n\nA Colorado [[grand jury]] voted in 1999 to indict the parents.<ref name=Martinez />{{efn|Burke testified at a 1999 grand jury hearing.<ref name=\"DC Burke gj\" /> Burke Ramsey's attorney, Jim Jenkins, sought to prevent his testifying at the grand jury and to eliminate him as a suspect,<ref name=\"DC Burke attny in town\">{{cite news |url=http://web.dailycamera.com/extra/ramsey/1999/20crmsy.html |title=Burke Ramsey's attorney in town: Brother of slain girl could be asked to give grand jury more information |newspaper= Daily Camera |date=May 20, 1999 |access-date=September 29, 2016}}</ref> but the DA's office said that Burke was not and never had been a suspect.<ref name=\"DC Not Burke\" /><ref name=\"DC Burke gj\" />}} The indictment cited \"two counts each of child abuse\" and said the parents \"did unlawfully, knowingly, recklessly and feloniously permit a child to be unreasonably placed in a situation that posed a threat of injury to the child's life or health, which resulted in the death of JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey, a child under the age of sixteen.\"<ref name=\"DP Indictment\">{{cite news | url=http://www.denverpost.com/2013/10/25/jonbent-ramsey-grand-jury-indictment-accused-parents-of-child-abuse-resulting-in-death/ | title=JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey grand jury indictment accused parents of child abuse resulting in death | newspaper=[[Denver Post]] | date=October 25, 2013 | access-date=September 26, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nAmong the experts who testified in the case were DNA specialist [[Barry Scheck]] and forensic expert [[Henry Lee (forensic scientist)|Dr. Henry Lee]].<ref name=\"HP Timeline\" /> On October 13, 1999, Alex Hunter, who was the district attorney at the time, refused to sign the indictment, saying that the evidence was insufficient for prosecution.<ref name=\"HP Timeline\" /><ref name=Martinez>{{cite news |first1=Michael |last1=Martinez |first2= Faith |last2= Karimi |url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/10/25/justice/jonbenet-ramsey-documents/ |title=Papers: Grand jury in 1999 sought to indict JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey's parents |publisher=CNN |date=October 25, 2013 |access-date=September 5, 2015}}</ref> The public thought that the grand jury investigation had been inconclusive.<ref>{{cite web |title=JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey grand jury voted to indict parents in 1999, but the District Attorney refused to prosecute| first= Charlie| last= Brennan| date= January 27, 2013| url=http://www.dailycamera.com/news/boulder/ci_22446410/boulder-grand-jury-voted-indict-ramseys|website= The Daily Camera|access-date=January 28, 2013}}</ref> In 2002, the statute of limitations on the grand jury's charges expired.<ref name=\"DP Indictment\" />\n\nThe grand jury's vote to indict was not revealed publicly until October 25, 2013, when previously sealed court documents were released.{{efn|In September 2013, ''[[Daily Camera]]'' reporter Charlie Brennan and the Reporters Committee for Freedom of the Press filed a lawsuit to press DA Stan Garnett to release the grand jury's indictment.<ref>{{cite news |last=Byars|first=Mitchell|title=Camera reporter sues Boulder DA seeking release of Ramsey indictment|url=http://www.dailycamera.com/news/boulder/ci_24124759/camera-reporter-sues-boulder-da-seeking-release-ramsey|newspaper=Boulder Daily Camera|date=September 18, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe police sought to interview Burke Ramsey again in September 2010, according to [[L. Lin Wood]], a high-profile [[libel]] (defamation) attorney whom the Ramsey family hired in 1999.<ref name=\"NW No Justice\"/><ref name=\"HP Timeline\" /> In 2012, the book ''Foreign Faction \u2013 Who Really Kidnapped JonBenet?'' by A. James Kolar, a former investigator under Boulder County District Attorney Lacy, was published. The book discounts the intruder theory and proposes scenarios of Ramsey family involvement in JonBen\u00e9t's death.<ref name=\"HP Timeline\" />\n\nIn mid-October 2013, a judge ruled that the DA must show why the indictment should remain sealed.<ref>{{cite web |last=Byars|first=Mitchell|title=Judge orders Boulder DA to show why Ramsey indictment should remain secret|url=http://www.dailycamera.com/news/boulder/ci_24331072/judge-orders-boulder-da-show-why-ramsey-indictment|website= Daily Camera}}</ref> ''[[The Denver Post]]'' (a sister paper of the ''Daily Camera'') published an editorial calling for the indictment to be unsealed.<ref>{{cite news|title=Editorial: Time to unseal indictment in JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey case |url=http://www.denverpost.com/ci_24354220/editorial-time-unseal-indictment-jonben-t-ramsey-case |newspaper=Denver Post |date=October 21, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131023061640/http://www.denverpost.com/ci_24354220/editorial-time-unseal-indictment-jonben-t-ramsey-case |archivedate=October 23, 2013 }}</ref>}}\n\n''[[The Case of: JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey]]'', a show broadcast on [[CBS]] on September 18 and 19, 2016, said that they used a group of experts to evaluate the evidence. The group theorized that Burke hit his sister in the head with a heavy object, perhaps not intending to kill her. They suggested that the ransom letter was an attempt to cover up the circumstances of JonBenet's death.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbs.com/shows/the-case-of-jonbenet-ramsey/|title=The Case of JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey|publisher=CBS|access-date=September 29, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160928102130/http://www.cbs.com/shows/the-case-of-jonbenet-ramsey/|archivedate=September 28, 2016}}</ref> On behalf of Burke Ramsey, his counsel Wood filed defamation lawsuits against CBS, the producers of the program, and several of its participants, based on many of its claims.<ref>[https://people.com/crime/burke-ramsey-jonbenet-cbs-series-lawsuit/ \"Burke Ramsey- JonBenet/ CBS series lawsuit\"], ''People'' magazine</ref>\n\n===Intruder theory===\nThe second theory is the intruder theory. The Ramseys developed a relationship with District Attorney Mary Lacy and her office, which was criticized by authorities such as the city's mayor, Leslie L Durgin.<ref name=\"NYP Morabito\"/><ref name=\"NYT Bungled\" />{{efn|The city's mayor Leslie L Durgin said, \"I'm extremely concerned about the relationship between the district attorney's office and the Ramsey attorneys. The perception is that they are closer than we thought.\" Ann Louise Bardach, ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'' journalist, wrote that there were weekly breakfast meetings between a Ramsey defense lawyer and Peter Hofstrom, the prosecutor's liaison to the Ramsey family.<ref name=\"NYT Bungled\" />}} Although the police may have still suspected the Ramseys, they and the prosecutors followed leads for intruders partly due to the unidentified boot mark left in the basement room where JonBen\u00e9t's body was found.<ref name=\"Newsweek 2016\"/> The police routinely ignored leads to any suspects outside of the family.<ref>https://www.cbsnews.com/news/jonbenet-dna-rules-out-parents/</ref>\n\nEarly suspects included neighbor Bill McReynolds, who played Santa Claus; former family housekeeper Linda Hoffmann-Pugh, and a man named Michael Helgoth, who died in an apparent [[suicide]] shortly after JonBen\u00e9t's death. Hundreds of DNA tests were performed to find a match to the DNA recovered during her autopsy.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/real-life/true-stories/santa-and-the-housekeeper-the-forgotten-jonbenet-suspects/news-story/c921605802d5086911a1a34780225a4d | title=Santa and the housekeeper: The forgotten JonBenet suspects | publisher=news.com.au | date=September 23, 2016 | access-date=September 29, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nSmit assessed the evidence and concluded that an intruder had committed the crime.<ref name=taha>{{cite news| last= Taha| first= Nadia | url= https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/14/us/14smit.html | title= Lou Smit, Detective in JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey Case, Is Dead at 75| work= [[The New York Times]]| date= August 13, 2010| access-date= August 14, 2010}}</ref> On the night JonBen\u00e9t was killed, there had been two windows that were left slightly open to allow for electrical cords for the outside Christmas lights to pass through, a broken basement window, and one unlocked door.<ref name=\"Maloney\" />{{efn|It was later determined that some windows and a door had been left unlocked that night. In addition, a basement window was previously broken by John Ramsey when he was locked out of the house.<ref name=\"Newsweek 2016\" />\n\n[[Lou Smit]], a retired and successful homicide detective, was brought in to investigate the case. He quickly became a proponent of the intruder theory, and believed that the intruder entered through this basement window. A suitcase was found on the floor almost directly underneath this window. Smit theorized the attacker(s) planned to use this suitcase either to take JonBen\u00e9t alive as a kidnap victim or move her body out of the house, but this proved impossible.<ref name=\"DC Smit theory\">{{cite news | url=http://web.dailycamera.com/extra/ramsey/2001/01lrams.html | title=Smit presents intruder theory | author=Christopher Anderson | newspaper=Daily Camera | date=May 1, 2001 | access-date=September 29, 2016 }}</ref>}} Smit's theory was that someone entered the Ramsey home through the broken basement window. This has been criticized because there was an intact cobweb in the basement window.<ref name=\"Time Inc.\"/> The steel grate that covered the window also had undisturbed cobwebs, and the foliage around the grate had been undisturbed.<ref name=\"Thomas and Davis\">{{cite book|vauthors=Thomas S, Davis DA|title =JonBenet: Inside the Ramsey Murder Investigation|isbn = 1429981733|publisher=[[St. Martin's Press]]|year=2011|pages=40, 48|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pC3k1vnwLhEC&pg=PA40&lpg=PA40}}</ref> There were also cobwebs in the tracks of various windows, and dust and debris were on some sills.<ref name=\"Thomas and Davis\"/> Smit believed that the intruder subdued JonBen\u00e9t using a stun gun and took her down to the basement. JonBen\u00e9t was killed and a ransom note was left.<ref name=\"RS\">{{cite news | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/news/3-big-ways-the-case-of-jonbenet-ramsey-got-it-wrong-w440970 | title=3 Big Ways 'The Case of: JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey' Got It Wrong | work=Rolling Stone | date=September 20, 2016 | author=Amelia McDonell-Parry | access-date=September 26, 2016 }}</ref> Smit's theory was supported by former FBI agent [[John E. Douglas]], who had been hired by the Ramsey family.<ref name=taha/>{{efn|In his book ''The Cases That Haunt Us'', former FBI agent [[John E. Douglas]] (hired by the Ramsey family) writes that he quibbled with a few of Smit's interpretations but generally agreed with his investigation and conclusions. Douglas particularly praised Smit's discovery in autopsy photos of what appeared to be previously overlooked evidence of a \"[[electroshock weapon|stun gun]]\" having been used to subdue JonBen\u00e9t.<ref name=taha/>}}  Believing that the Ramseys were innocent, Smit resigned from the investigation on September 20, 1998, five days after the grand jury was convened against the Ramseys.<ref name=\"HP Timeline\" /> While no longer an official investigator on the case, Smit continued to work on it until his death in 2010.<ref name=taha/>\n\nStephen Singular, author of the book ''Presumed Guilty: An Investigation into the JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey Case, the Media and the Culture of Pornography'' (2016), refers to consultations with cyber-crime specialists who believe that JonBen\u00e9t, due to her beauty pageant experience, could have attracted the attention of [[Child pornography|child pornographers]] and [[Pedophilia|pedophiles]].<ref>{{citation |title= The Pornography Connection |first= Patrick |last= Bellamy}}</ref>\n\nIt was determined that there had been more than 100 burglaries in the Ramseys' neighborhood in the months before JonBen\u00e9t's murder. There were 38 registered [[sex offender]]s living within a two-mile (3&nbsp;km) radius of the Ramseys' home.<ref name= CBSLeung2004>{{cite web|last1=Leung|first1=Rebecca|title=JonBenet: DNA Rules Out Parents| url= http://www.cbsnews.com/news/jonbenet-dna-rules-out-parents/|website=CBS News|access-date=August 10, 2016| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160115025353/http://www.cbsnews.com/news/jonbenet-dna-rules-out-parents/|archivedate=January 15, 2016| date= December 16, 2004}}</ref> In 2001, former Boulder County prosecutor Trip DeMuth and Boulder County Sheriff's Detective Steve Ainsworth stated that there should be a more aggressive investigation of the intruder theory.<ref name=\"DC Smit theory\"/>\n\nOne of the individuals whom Smit identified as a suspect was Gary Howard Oliva, who was arrested for \"two counts of attempted sexual exploitation of a child and one count of sexual exploitation of a child\" charges in June 2016, according to Boulder's ''[[Daily Camera]]''. Oliva, a registered sex offender, was publicly identified as a suspect in an October 2002 episode of ''[[48 Hours (TV series)|48 Hours Investigates]]''.<ref name=Oliva>{{cite news | url=http://www.dailycamera.com/news/boulder/ci_30041518/jonbenet-ramsey-murder-suspect-gary-oliva-charged-boulder-child-porn-case | title=Ramsey murder suspect charged in Boulder child porn case | author=Charlie Brennan | date=June 21, 2016 | access-date=September 28, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n''The Killing of JonBen\u00e9t: The Truth Uncovered'', broadcast by [[A&E (TV network)|A&E]] on September 5, 2016, concluded that an unidentified male was responsible for JonBen\u00e9t's death, based on forensic DNA analysis of evidence. In the documentary, Dr. Lawrence Kobilinsky stated that \"an unidentified male committed this crime\".<ref>{{ cite news | url=http://www.thedenverchannel.com/news/front-range/boulder/new-details-revealed-about-jonbenet-ramseys-murder-in-ae-documentary | title=New details revealed about JonBenet Ramsey's murder in A&E documentary | author=Jennifer Kovaleski | date=September 6, 2016 | access-date= September 30, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nThe District Attorney's office investigating pedophiles indicated to former Denver prosecutor Craig Silverman that the District Attorney's office followed the intruder theory. Silverman said, \"Once you have conceded the possibility of an intruder, I don't see how any Ramsey could ever be successfully prosecuted.\"<ref name=\"NYT Bungled\" /> Gordon Coombes joined the office as an investigator under Lacy when they were testing JonBen\u00e9t's clothing for touch DNA. He also said that Lacy strongly supported the intruder theory and talked about it with the staff. Although he was not directly involved with the case, he said he was told not to voice opposition to the theory because he might lose his job. \"It just seemed weird the whole premise of ... this attempt to influence the entire agency,\" he stated.<ref name=\"NYP Morabito\" />\n\n==False confession==\nJohn Mark Karr, a 41-year-old elementary school teacher, was arrested in [[Bangkok]], [[Thailand]], on August 15, 2006 when he [[false confession|falsely confessed]] to murdering JonBen\u00e9t.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Ferguson |first=Zoe |title=Where Is John Mark Karr, The Man Who Falsely Confessed to JonBenet Ramsey's Murder, & What Is He Doing Now? |url=https://www.bustle.com/articles/72098-where-is-john-mark-karr-the-man-who-falsely-confessed-to-jonbenet-ramseys-murder-what |date=26 March 2015 |access-date=1 July 2017 |magazine=[[Bustle (magazine)|Bustle]]}}</ref> He claimed that he had drugged, sexually assaulted, and accidentally killed her.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/14379566/ns/us_news-crime_and_courts/t/suspect-jonbenet-ramseys-death-accident/|title=Suspect: JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey's death 'an accident'|date=August 17, 2006|website=NBCNews.com|accessdate=November 19, 2014}}</ref>  According to [[CNN]], \"Authorities also said they did not find any evidence linking [Karr] to the crime scene.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2006/LAW/10/16/karr.interview/ |work=CNN |title=Karr: 'I've never harmed a child'}}</ref><ref name=\"CNN Karr\" />\n\nIn his confession, Karr had provided only basic facts that were publicly known and failed to provide any convincing details. His claim that he had drugged JonBen\u00e9t was doubted because the autopsy indicated that no drugs were found in her body.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.denverpost.com/news/ci_4190797 |title=Experts incredulous over JonBen\u00e9t confession |last1=Martin |first1=Claire |last2=Simpson |first2=Kevin |date=August 17, 2006 |website=DenverPost.com |access-date=November 19, 2014}}</ref> DNA samples that were taken from Karr did not match DNA found on JonBen\u00e9t's body.<ref name=\"CNN Karr\">{{cite news |url= http://www.cnn.com/2006/LAW/08/28/ramsey.arrest/index.html |title=No DNA match, no JonBen\u00e9t charges |website=CNN.com |date=August 28, 2006|access-date=June 22, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.findlaw.com/hdocs/docs/karr/cokarr82806mq.html |title=Not the source of the DNA found |website=Findlaw.com |date=August 22, 2006 |access-date=June 22, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.findlaw.com/hdocs/docs/karr/cokarr82806mq.html |title=D.A.'s Motion to Quash Arrest Warrant |website= Findlaw.com |date=August 22, 2006|access-date=June 22, 2011}}</ref>{{efn|Authorities had tracked Karr down by using the [[Internet]] after [[email]]s were sent regarding the case to [[Michael Tracey]], a journalism professor at the [[University of Colorado at Boulder|University of Colorado]].<ref>{{cite web|date=August 17, 2006 |url=http://www.crimelibrary.com/news/original/0806/1703_ramsey_arrest_john_karr.html |title=No Forensic Evidence Currently Links John Karr to JonBen\u00e9t Murder |publisher=Crime Library |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060901231718/http://www.crimelibrary.com/news/original/0806/1703_ramsey_arrest_john_karr.html |archivedate=September 1, 2006 }}</ref> After Karr was arrested and brought back to the US, he was released to face extradition for [[child pornography]] charges that originated in [[Sonoma County, California]]. These charges against him were subsequently dismissed<ref name=\"CNN Karr\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,1543277,00.html|title=John Mark Karr's Child Porn Case Dismissed|date=October 5, 2006|website=People.com|access-date=November 19, 2014}}</ref> due to lack of evidence.<ref name=\"HP Timeline\" /> While he was under investigation, the press coverage of Karr's false confession was described as a [[media frenzy]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/nation/2006-08-18-ramsey-thailand_x.htm|title=JonBen\u00e9t slaying suspect returning to U.S., media frenzy|website=USAToday.com|access-date=September 16, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/world/archives/2006/08/30/2003325488|title=Media frenzy over Karr shows nothing's changed|website=Taipeitimes.com |access-date=September 16, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.editorandpublisher.com/PrintArticle/Karr-Cleared-in-JonBenet-Case-After-Media-Frenzy |title= Karr Cleared in JonBen\u00e9t Case - After Media Frenzy |website=Editorandpublisher.com |date=August 28, 2006|access-date=June 9, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2006-09-07/news/0609070022_1_john-mark-karr-wilson-story-joseph-wilson |work=Chicago Tribune |first=Jonah |last=Goldberg |title=Media frenzy, facts collide |date=September 7, 2006}}</ref>}}\n\n==Defamation lawsuits==\nLin Wood, the Ramseys' family libel attorney, filed [[defamation]] lawsuits against several people and companies that had reported on the case, starting in 1999.  They sued ''[[Star (magazine)|Star]]'' magazine and its parent company [[American Media (publisher)|American Media, Inc.]] on their son's behalf in 1999.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://web.dailycamera.com/extra/ramsey/1999/01crams.html | title=Ramseys sue Star on behalf of son: Libel suit seeks $25 million in damages against tabloid | author=Shelley Hill | newspaper=Daily Camera | location=Boulder, Colorado | date=December 1, 1999 | access-date=October 11, 2016 }}</ref> Defamation suits have been filed by the Ramseys and their friends against several unnamed media outlets.<ref>{{ cite news | url=http://fox6now.com/2015/02/25/jonbenet-ramsey-murder-case-former-police-chief-opens-up-on-reddit-and-now-apparently-regrets-remarks/ | title=JonBenet Ramsey murder case: Former police chief opens up on Reddit, and now apparently regrets remarks | publisher=Fox6 Now | date=February 25, 2015 | access-date=October 11, 2016 }}</ref> A defamation suit was filed in 2001 against the authors and publisher of ''JonBen\u00e9t: Inside the Ramsey Murder Investigation'' (2000). The suit against Don Davis, Steven Thomas, and [[St. Martin's Press]] was settled out of court the following year.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.thedenverchannel.com/news/ramseys-settle-book-libel-suit | title=Ramseys Settle Book Libel Suit: Former Boulder Detective Settles Case Out Of Court | date=March 20, 2002 | publisher=7NEWS & TheDenverChannel.com | access-date=October 11, 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171011022521/http://www.thedenverchannel.com/news/ramseys-settle-book-libel-suit | archive-date=October 11, 2017 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nJohn and Patsy Ramsey were sued in two defamation lawsuits arising from the publication of their book, ''The Death of Innocence'' (2001). These suits were brought by two persons named in the book who were said to have been investigated by Boulder police as suspects in the case. The Ramseys were defended in those lawsuits by Lin Wood and three other Atlanta attorneys, James C. Rawls, Eric P. Schroeder, and S. Derek Bauer. They obtained the dismissal of both lawsuits.  U.S. District Court Judge Julie Carnes later concluded that \"abundant evidence\" in the murder case pointed to an intruder having committed the crime.<ref>{{cite web |first= R. Robin |last= McDonald |url=http://www.law.com/jsp/nlj/PubArticleNLJ.jsp?id=1202429072171&slreturn=1&hbxlogin=1 |title= Northern District of Georgia's New Chief Judge Reflects on Her Career |website=Law.com |date=March 16, 2009| access-date= June 22, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2006, Rod Westmoreland, a friend of John Ramsey, filed a defamation suit against an anonymous web surfer who had posted two messages on Internet forums using the pseudonym \"undertheradar\" implicating Westmoreland in the murder.<ref>{{cite web |author= Time Waster |url=http://www.thesmokinggun.com/archive/1109061jonbenet1.html |title=Man Sues Over JonBen\u00e9t Murder Claim |website=Thesmokinggun.com |date=November 9, 2006|access-date=June 22, 2011}}</ref>\n\nDuring a September 2016 interview with [[WWJ-TV|CBS Detroit]] and in ''[[The Case of: JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey]]'' documentary television program, forensic pathologist [[Dr. Werner Spitz]] accused Burke Ramsey of killing his sister.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://time.com/4522966/jonbenet-ramsey-brother-sues/|title=JonBenet Ramsey's Brother Files $150 Million Defamation Suit|last=Chan|first=Melissa|website=TIME.com|access-date=October 8, 2016}}</ref> On October 6, 2016, Burke filed a defamation lawsuit against Spitz. Burke and his attorneys, who include Lin Wood, sought a total of $150 million in punitive and compensatory damages. Wood said he would also file a suit against CBS at the end of October 2016.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://denver.cbslocal.com/2016/10/07/burke-ramsey-sues-investigator-who-accused-him-of-killing-sister/ | title=Burke Ramsey Sues Investigator Who Accused Him Of Killing Sister | author=Marcia Garcia | publisher=CBS4 New Denver |date=October 7, 2016 | access-date=October 11, 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n |url=https://www.12news.com/article/news/nation-now/jonbenet-ramseys-brother-files-defamation-suit-against-pathologist/75-329918958 \n |title=JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey's brother files defamation suit against pathologist \n |agency=Associated Press \n |publisher=12 News \n |location=Arizona \n |date=October 7, 2016 \n |access-date=September 15, 2018\n}}</ref>\n\nOn December 28, 2016, Burke Ramsey's lawyers filed an additional civil lawsuit that accused [[CBS]], the production company Critical Content LLC, and seven experts and consultants of [[United States defamation law|defamation of character]]. They sought $250 million in compensatory damages and $500 million in punitive damages.<ref>{{cite news|author=Chris Harris |url=http://people.com/crime/burke-ramsey-jonbenet-cbs-series-lawsuit/ |title=JonBenet Ramsey's Brother Burke Sues CBS for $750 Million |website=People.com |date=December 29, 2016 |access-date=March 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, a judge denied the CBS motion to dismiss, and the suit was allowed to proceed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://money.cnn.com/2018/01/06/media/jonbenet-ramsey-brother-cbs-documentary/index.html|title=Judge allows lawsuit against CBS by brother of JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey to proceed|first1=Jackie|last1=Wattles|date=2018-01-06|access-date=2018-12-26}}</ref> In January 2019, Wood announced that the lawsuit had been settled \"to the satisfaction of all parties.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-jonbenet-lawsuit-settlement-idUSKCN1OY1XP|title=JonBenet Ramsey's brother settles lawsuit with CBS: attorney|date=2019-01-04|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-01-04|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Colorado}}\n* ''[[The Case of: JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey]]''\n* ''[[Casting JonBenet]]''\n* ''[[Getting Away with Murder: The JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey Mystery]]''\n* [[Paulette Gebara Farah]]\n* [[List of murdered American children]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n<!---- sorted by year, then author's last name ---->\n* {{cite book | author=Carlton Smith | title=Death of a Little Princess: The Tragic Story of the Murder of JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey | location=New York | publisher= St. Martin's Paperbacks | year= 1997 | isbn=0312964331 }}\n* {{cite book | author= Linda Edison McLean with foreword by [[Patsy Ramsey]]| title=JonBen\u00e9t's Mother: The Tragedy and the Truth | location=Parsons, WV | publisher=McClain Print Co. | year= 1998 | isbn=0870125966}}\n* {{cite book | author=Eleanor Von Duyke and Dwight Wallington | title=A Little Girl's Dream? A JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey Story | location=Austin, TX | publisher=Windsor House | year=1998 | isbn=1881636445 }}\n* {{cite book | author=[[Cyril Wecht|Cyril H. Wecht]] and Charles Bosworth, Jr. | title=Who Killed JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey? | location=New York | publisher=Onyx Book | year=1998 | isbn=0451408713 | url=https://archive.org/details/whokilledjonbene00wech }}\n* {{cite book |author=[[Lawrence Schiller]] | title=[[Perfect Murder, Perfect Town]]: The Uncensored Story of the JonBen\u00e9t Murder and the Grand Jury's Search for the Final Truth  | location=New York |publisher=HarperCollins | year=1999 | isbn=0060191538 }}\n* {{cite book | author=Stephen Singular | title=Presumed Guilty: An Investigation into the JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey Case, the Media, and the Culture of Pornography | location=Beverly Hills, CA | publisher=New Millennium Press | year=1999 | isbn=1893224007 | url=https://archive.org/details/presumedguiltyin00sing }}\n* {{cite book | author=[[John E. Douglas]] and [[Mark Olshaker]] | chapter=The JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey Murder | title=[[The Cases That Haunt Us]] | location=New York | publisher= Scribner | year=2000 | isbn=978-0-684-84600-2 }}\n* {{cite book | author=Steve Thomas and Don Davis | title=JonBen\u00e9t: Inside the Ramsey Murder Investigation | location=New York | publisher=St. Martin's Press | year=2000 | isbn=0312253265 | url=https://archive.org/details/jonbentinsider00thom }}\n* {{ cite book | title=The Death of Innocence: JonBen\u00e9t's Parents Tell Their Story | author=[[John Bennett Ramsey|John Ramsey]] and [[Patsy Ramsey]] | location=New York | publisher=Onyx | year=2001 | isbn=0451409736 }}\n* {{cite book | title=JonBenet: The Police Files |editor=Don Gentile and David Wright | location=Boca Raton, FL | publisher=American Media | year=2003 | isbn=1932270035 }}\n* {{cite book | author=A. James Kolar | title=Foreign Faction: Who Really Kidnapped JonBen\u00e9t?&nbsp;\u2013 A Former Lead Investigator Breaks Six Years of Silence | location=Telluride, CO | publisher=Ventus Publishing | year=2012 | isbn=0984763201 }}\n* {{cite book | author=Paula Woodward | title=We Have Your Daughter: The Unsolved Murder of JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey Twenty Years Later | publisher=Prospecta Press | year=2016 | isbn=1632260778}}\n<!---- sorted by year, then author's last name ---->\n\n===Articles===\n* {{cite news | url=http://web.dailycamera.com/extra/ramsey/1997/03/03-1.html | title=Police question Boulder 'Santa,' wife | agency=Associated Press | date=March 3, 1997 | newspaper=Daily Camera }}\n* {{cite news | url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3577037/He-hellraiser-JonBenet-Ramsey-private-investigator-opens-man-responsible-6-year-old-pageant-queen-s-1996-murder-killed-just-months-crime.html | title='He was a hellraiser': JonBenet Ramsey private investigator opens up about man who may be responsible for six-year-old pageant queen's 1996 murder who killed himself just months after the crime | date=May 6, 2016 | author=Ashley Collman | newspaper=Daily Mail }}\n* {{cite journal | url=http://www.crimemagazine.com/murder-jonben%C3%A9t-ramsey | title=The Murder of JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey | publisher=Crime Magazine | author=J.J. Maloney | date=October 25, 2013 | access-date=November 19, 2014 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129041656/http://www.crimemagazine.com/murder-jonben%C3%A9t-ramsey | archive-date=November 29, 2014 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}\n* {{cite magazine | url=http://www.westword.com/2006-10-12/news/made-for-each-other/full/ | title=Made for Each Other: The Karr fiasco is over, but Michael Tracey's quest for unlikely suspects in the Ramsey case goes on and on | author=Alan Prendergast | magazine=Westword | date=October 12, 2006 }}\n* {{ cite news | url=http://web.dailycamera.com/extra/ramsey/1999/17arsid.html | title=Police sought mom's arrest | author=Matt Sebastian | newspaper=Daily Camera | date=February 17, 1999  }}\n* {{cite news | url=http://web.dailycamera.com/extra/ramsey/1998/07thomle.html | title=The Thomas resignation letter - \"We were trying to deliver a murder case with hands tied behind our backs.\" | author=Steve Thomas | date=August 6, 1998| newspaper=Daily Camera }}\n\n===Videos===\n* {{cite episode\n | title = City under siege: The news media's coverage and Boulder officials' secretive handling of the investigation into the murder of JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey\n | series =[[Nightline]]\n | network =ABC\n | air-date =January 31, 1997\n| lccn=00568713}}\n* {{cite episode\n | title = Case Closed: The Boulder Police Department's investigation into murder of JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey\n | series =[[Nightline]]\n | network =ABC\n | air-date =May 30, 1997\n| lccn=00571015}}\n* {{cite AV media | title=[[Getting Away with Murder: The JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey Mystery]] | people= Edward Lucas, director | year=2000 | publisher=Fox Broadcasting Company |medium=television | lccn=2003632300}}\n* {{cite AV media | title=Investigative reports. Jon Ben\u00e9t \u2013 anatomy of an investigation | publisher= A&E Television Networks | people=[[Bill Kurtis]], executive producer| year=2000 | medium=television | lccn=2001646808}}\n* {{cite episode \n| series=[[Haunting Evidence]]\n | title=JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey\n | publisher=Court TV \n| air-date=October 4, 2008 \n| lccn=2009595419 \n| medium=television }}\n* {{cite AV media | title=[[The Case of: JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey]] | publisher=Critical Content (CBS broadcaster) | year=2016 | people=Jim Clemente, Laura Richards, Stan Burke, James Fitzgerald, James Kolar, [[Henry Lee (forensic scientist)|Henry Lee]], [[Cyril Wecht]], [[Werner Spitz]] | medium=television  }}\n* {{cite AV media | title=The Killing of JonBen\u00e9t: The Truth Uncovered | publisher=Mills Productions  for [[A&E (TV network)|A&E]] network| people=David Mills and Janet Taylor, executive producers for Mill Productions |medium=television | date=September 5, 2016 }}\n* [[Netflix]] released a documentary on the case ''[[Casting JonBenet]]'' on April 28, 2017.\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|2338600|JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey}}\n*{{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20000817061102/http://www.abcnews.go.com/sections/us/DailyNews/ramsey_index.html|date=August 17, 2000|title=Complete Coverage: The JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey Case }} - index of articles from [[ABC News]]\n{{Portal bar|Colorado|Biography|Law|1990s}}\n{{Authority control}}\n<!--All categories related to the girl go to the redirect. These categories should be related to the event.-->\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ramsey, JonBen\u00e9t}}\n[[Category:JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey]]\n[[Category:1996 in Colorado]]\n[[Category:1996 murders in the United States]]\n[[Category:Murder in Colorado]]\n[[Category:Unsolved murders in the United States]]\n[[Category:December 1996 crimes]]\n[[Category:December 1996 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:Deaths by person in the United States]]\n[[Category:Deaths by strangulation in the United States]]\n[[Category:Female murder victims]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|death of American child beauty queen}}{{Redirect|JonBen\u00e9t|the American noise rock outfit from Houston, Texas|The Jonben\u00e9t}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               =  JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey\n| image              =  Jonbenet-ramsey.jpg\n| image_upright =\n| image_size = <!-- DISCOURAGED per WP:IMGSIZE. Use image_upright. -->\n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = JonBen\u00e9t Patricia Ramsey\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1990|08|06|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place        = [[Atlanta|Atlanta, Georgia]], U.S.\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|1996|12|25|1990|08|06}}\n| death_place        = [[Boulder, Colorado]], U.S.\n| death_cause        = [[Asphyxia]] by strangulation<br />Craniocerebral trauma\n| resting_place      = [[St. James Episcopal Cemetery]]<br />[[Marietta, Georgia]], U.S.\n| resting_place_coordinates =  {{coord|33.95501|-84.55637}}\n| parents             = [[John Bennett Ramsey|John Ramsey]]<br />[[Patsy Ramsey]]\n}}\n\n'''JonBen\u00e9t Patricia Ramsey''' (August 6, 1990 \u2013 December 25, 1996) was an [[Americans|American]] [[child beauty pageant|child beauty queen]] who was killed at the age of 6 in her family's home in [[Boulder, Colorado]]. A lengthy handwritten [[ransom]] note was found in the house. Her father [[John Bennett Ramsey|John]] found the girl's body in the basement of their house about eight hours after she had been reported [[missing person|missing]]. She sustained a broken skull from a blow to the head and had been strangled; a [[garrote]] was found tied around her neck. The [[autopsy]] report stated that the official cause of death was \"[[asphyxia]] by [[Strangling|strangulation]] associated with [[Traumatic brain injury|craniocerebral trauma]].\"<ref name=\"Klaver\">{{cite book |last= Klaver| first= Elizabeth |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tUgF9udmFuEC&pg=PA2|title=Sites of Autopsy in Contemporary Culture|year=2012|publisher=SUNY Press| isbn=0-791-48342-8 |page=2}}</ref><ref name=AutopsyReport/> Her death was ruled a [[homicide]].<ref name=\"Chan\"/> The case generated nationwide public and media interest, in part because her mother [[Patsy Ramsey]] (herself a former beauty queen) had entered JonBen\u00e9t into a series of [[child beauty pageant]]s. The crime is still unsolved and remains an open investigation with the Boulder Police Department.\n\nThe police initially suspected that the ransom note had been written by JonBen\u00e9t's mother, and that the note and appearance of the child's body had been staged by her parents in order to cover up the crime. However, in 1998, the [[District Attorney]] (DA) said that due to a new [[DNA]] analysis, none of the immediate family members were under suspicion for the crime.<ref name=\"9news.com\">{{cite web|first=Mary T. |last=Lacy |date=July 9, 2008 |title=Twentieth Judicial District, District Attorney's Office, Letter to John Ramsey |url=http://www.9news.com/pdfs/ramseyDA.pdf |archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20081218174842/http://www.9news.com/pdfs/ramseyDA.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=December 18, 2008|publisher=[[KUSA (TV)|KUSA 9 News]] |location=Denver, Colorado |format=PDF |access-date=September 5, 2015 }}</ref> Also in 1998, the police and the DA both said that JonBen\u00e9t's brother Burke, who was nine years old at the time of her death, was not a suspect.<ref name=\"DC Not Burke\" /><ref name=\"DC Burke gj\" /> The Ramseys gave several televised interviews but resisted police questioning except on their own terms. In October 2013, unsealed court documents revealed that a 1999 [[grand jury]] had recommended filing charges against JonBen\u00e9t's parents for permitting the child to be in a threatening situation. John and Patsy were also accused of hindering the [[prosecution]] of an unidentified person who had \"committed ... the crime of [[first-degree murder|murder in the first degree]] and [[child abuse]] resulting in death\".<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/10/25/justice/jonbenet-ramsey-documents/index.html|title=Papers: Grand jury in 1999 sought to indict JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey's parents|first1=Michael|last1=Martinez|first2=Faith|last2=Karimi|publisher=CNN|date=October 25, 2013}}</ref> However, the DA determined that there was insufficient evidence to pursue a successful [[indictment]].<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nIn 2002, the DA's successor took over investigation of the case from the police and primarily pursued the theory that an intruder had committed the killing. In 2003, trace DNA that was taken from the victim's clothes was found to belong to an unknown male; each of the family's DNA had been excluded from this match. The DA sent the Ramseys a letter of apology in 2008, declaring the family \"completely cleared\" by the DNA results.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/video/playerIndex?id=5349856 |title=JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey's Parents Cleared |publisher=[[ABC News]] |date=July 10, 2008 |access-date=September 5, 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130609061202/http://abcnews.go.com/video/playerIndex?id=5349856 |archivedate=June 9, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Others, including former Boulder police chief Mark Beckner, disagreed with exonerating the Ramseys, criticizing exonerating anyone based on a small piece of evidence that has not yet been proven to be connected.<ref name=\"Time Inc.\">{{cite book|authors =The Editors of People|title =PEOPLE True Crimes: Cases That Shocked America|isbn =1683305167 |publisher=[[Time Inc. Books]]|year=2016|pages=9\u201311|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=heSiDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA9&lpg=PA9}}</ref><ref name=\"NYP Morabito\">{{cite news | url=https://nypost.com/2016/09/12/jonbenet-ramsey-series-questions-key-dna-evidence/ | title=JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey series questions key DNA evidence | author=Andrea Morabito | date=September 12, 2016  | access-date=September 28, 2016 | newspaper=New York Post }}</ref> In February 2009, the Boulder police took the case back from the DA and reopened the investigation.<ref name= bonus>{{cite news |first=Vanessa |last=Miller |date=February 2, 2009 |url=http://www.coloradodaily.com/ci_13112748 |title=Boulder police take back Ramsey case |work=[[Colorado Daily]] |access-date=September 5, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923205547/http://www.coloradodaily.com/ci_13112748 |archive-date=September 23, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nMedia coverage of the case has focused on JonBen\u00e9t's brief beauty pageant career, as well as her parents' wealth and the unusual evidence found in the case. Media reports questioned how the police handled the case. Ramsey family members and their friends have filed [[defamation]] suits against several media organizations.\n\n==Life and interment==\n[[File:JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey grave.jpg|right|220px|thumb|JonBen\u00e9t's grave at Saint James Episcopal Cemetery in Marietta, Georgia.]]\nJonBen\u00e9t Ramsey was born in 1990 in [[Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], the younger of two children of Patricia (1956\u20132006)<ref>{{cite news |last1=Reed |first1=Christopher |title=Obituary: Patsy Ramsey |url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2006/jun/27/guardianobituaries.usa |access-date=September 15, 2018 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=June 28, 2006}}</ref> and John Ramsey (1943\u2013). She had an older brother named Burke (1987\u2013).<ref name=\"People1997\">{{cite journal |last= Jerome| first= Richard| date= October 6, 1997| title= Mystery Couple|url=http://people.com/archive/cover-story-mystery-couple-vol-48-no-14/|journal=People|publisher=Time Inc.| volume= 48|issue=14|issn=0093-7673}}</ref> Her first name combines her father's first and middle names, and her mother's first name was used as her middle name. JonBen\u00e9t was enrolled in [[kindergarten]] at [[Boulder Valley School District|High Peaks Elementary School]] in [[Boulder, Colorado|Boulder]], [[Colorado]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Schiller|first=Lawrence |title=Perfect Murder, Perfect Town|url=https://archive.org/details/perfectmurderper00schi|url-access=registration|year=1999|publisher=HarperCollins|isbn=0-060-19153-8|page=[https://archive.org/details/perfectmurderper00schi/page/38 38]}}</ref>\n\nJonBen\u00e9t's body was found on December 26, 1996 in her family home in Boulder, Colorado. She was buried at [[St. James Episcopal Cemetery]] in [[Marietta, Georgia]]. She was interred next to her much older half-sister Elizabeth Pasch Ramsey, who had died in a car crash four years earlier at age 22.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Williams|first=Paige|date=October 2006|title=Grave Faith|journal=Atlanta Magazine|publisher=Emmis Communications|volume=46|issue=6|pages=84, 87|issn=0004-6701|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rQ8AAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA82}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1997-02-21/news/9702210074_1_jonbenet-ramsey-ramsey-investigation-boulder-police |title= Reports Sought In Jonbenet's Sister's Death|last=McSherry Breslin| first= Meg|date=February 21, 1997 |website=ChicagoTribune.com |access-date= November 19, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Parents==\n[[John Bennett Ramsey|John Ramsey]] was a businessman who was the president of Access Graphics, a computer system company that later became a subsidiary of [[Lockheed Martin]].<ref name= hewitt>{{cite journal |last=Hewitt|first=Bill|date=January 20, 1997|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20143261,00.html |title= Lost Innocent|journal=People|publisher=Time Inc.| volume= 47| issue=2| issn=0093-7673}}</ref> His first marriage ended in [[divorce]] in 1978. His two surviving adult children (a son and a daughter) lived elsewhere. His 22-year-old daughter from the first marriage, Elizabeth, died in a 1992 car crash.<ref name=\"NW No Justice\"/>\n\nIn 1991, John had moved with his second wife and family to Boulder, where Access Graphics' headquarters was located.<ref name=inside>{{cite book |last1= Thomas| first1=Steve |last2=Davis|first2=Donald A.|title=JonBenet: Inside the Ramsey Murder Investigation| year= 2011| publisher= Macmillan|isbn=9781429981736}}</ref>\n \nPatricia \"Patsy\" Ramsey entered their daughter in various [[child beauty pageant]]s that were held in Boulder.<ref name= hewitt /> JonBen\u00e9t won the titles of America's Royale Miss, Little Miss Charlevoix, Little Miss Colorado, Colorado State All-Star Kids Cover Girl, and National Tiny Miss Beauty.<ref name=fast-facts>{{cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/08/29/us/jonbenet-ramsey-murder-fast-facts/|title=JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey Murder Fast Facts|date=October 28, 2014|website=Cnn.com|access-date=November 19, 2014}}</ref> JonBen\u00e9t's active role in child beauty pageants and Patsy's reported \"[[stage mother|pageant mother]]\" behavior were reported by the media after the murder.<ref name=\"People1997\"/>\n\nIn the summer of 1997\u2014approximately six months after JonBen\u00e9t's death\u2014the Ramseys moved to a new home in Atlanta after a summer at their vacation retreat in [[Charlevoix, Michigan]].<ref name=\"HP Timeline\" /> Patsy died of [[ovarian cancer]] at age 49 in 2006; she was interred next to her daughter.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.cnn.com/2006-06-24/justice/ramsey.death_1_jonbenet-ovarian-cancer-john-ramsey?_s=PM:LAW |work=CNN |title=Patsy Ramsey, JonBenet's mother, dies |date=June 24, 2006 |access-date=September 14, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151001012629/http://www.cnn.com/2006/LAW/06/24/ramsey.death/index.html?_s=PM%3ALAW |archivedate=October 1, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Evidence==\n===Ransom note===\n[[File:JonBenet Ramsey ransom note.jpg|thumb|The ransom note]]<!--\n{{Quote box |width=30em |bgcolor=#c6dbf7 |align=right |title= Text of the ransom note |quote=Mr. Ramsey,<br /><br />Listen carefully! We are a group of individuals that represent a small foreign faction. We <s>do</s> respect your {{sic|bus|siness}} but not the country that it serves. At this time we have your daughter in our {{sic|po|session}}. She is safe and unharmed and if you want her to see 1997, you must follow our instructions to the letter.<br /><br />You will withdraw $118,000.00 from your account. $100,000 will be in $100 bills and the remaining $18,000 in $20 bills. Make sure that you bring an adequate size attache to the bank. When you get home you will put the money in a brown paper bag. I will call you between 8 and 10 am tomorrow to instruct you on delivery. The delivery will be exhausting so I advise you to be rested. If we monitor you getting the money early, we might call you early to arrange an earlier delivery of the money and hence a {{sic}} earlier <s>delivery</s> pick-up of your daughter.<br /><br />Any deviation of my instructions will result in the immediate execution of your daughter. You will also be denied her remains for proper burial. The two gentlemen watching over your daughter do <sup>not</sup> particularly like you so I advise you not to provoke them. Speaking to anyone about your situation, such as Police, F.B.I., etc., will result in your daughter being beheaded. If we catch you talking to a stray dog, she dies. If you alert bank authorities, she dies. If the money is in any way marked or tampered with, she dies. You will be scanned for electronic devices and if any are found, she dies. You can try to deceive us but be warned that we are familiar with law enforcement countermeasures and tactics. You stand a 99% chance of killing your daughter if you try to out smart {{sic}} us. Follow our instructions and you stand a 100% chance of getting her back.<br /><br />You and your family are under constant scrutiny as well as the authorities. Don't try to grow a brain John. You are not the only fat cat around so don't think that killing will be difficult. Don't underestimate us John. Use that good southern common sense of yours. It is up to you now John!<br /><br />Victory!<br /><br />S.B.T.C|source=[https://web.archive.org/web/20061208031500/http://www.thedenverchannel.com/2006/0818/9699449.jpg Original text]}}-->\n\nAccording to statements that Patsy gave to authorities on December 26, 1996, she realized that her daughter was [[missing person|missing]] after she found a two-and-a-half-page handwritten [[ransom]] note on the kitchen staircase. The note demanded {{US$|118000|1996}}.<ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/US/9701/21/ramsey.update/index.html |title=Police drop some potential suspects in Ramsey killing|website=CNN.com |date=January 21, 1997 |access-date=June 22, 2011}}</ref> John pointed out to police first on the scene that the amount was nearly identical to his Christmas bonus of the prior year, which suggested that someone who would have access to that information would be involved in the crime. Investigators looked at several theories behind the dollar amount demanded. They considered employees at Access Graphics who may have known of the amount of John's prior bonus. They also considered the possibility that the ransom demand was a reference to [[Psalm 118]], and spoke to religious sources to determine possible relevance.<ref>Schiller, Lawrence (1999). ''Perfect Murder, Perfect Town'', p. 323, p. 447.  HarperCollins, New York. {{ISBN|0-06-109696-2}}</ref>\n\nThe ransom note was unusually long. The [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] told the police that it was very unusual for such a note to be written at the crime scene.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://fox2now.com/2015/02/26/jonbenet-ramsey-case-10-things-the-ex-police-chief-just-revealed/ | title=JonBenet Ramsey case: 9 things the ex-police chief just revealed | author=CNN Wires | publisher=Fox2News | date=February 26, 2015 | access-date=October 2, 2016 }}</ref> The police believed that the note was staged, because it did not have any fingerprints except for Patsy's and authorities who had handled it,<ref name=\"Time Inc.\"/> and because it included an unusual use of exclamation marks and initialisms.<ref name=\"Expers dissect\">{{cite news | url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/video/9271998-experts-dissect-jonbenet-ramsey-ransom-note-29249678 | title=Experts Dissect JonBenet Ramsey Ransom Note | date=September 27, 1998 | publisher=ABC News | access-date=October 2, 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.thedenverchannel.com/news/front-range/boulder/jonbenet-ramsey-case-former-boulder-police-chief-mark-beckner-says-police-botched-initial-handling | title=JonBenet Ramsey case: Former Boulder police chief Mark Beckner says police botched initial handling | author=Associated Press, Deb Stanley | publisher=The Denver Channel, local ABC station | date=February 25, 2015 | access-date=October 2, 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201080750/http://www.thedenverchannel.com/news/front-range/boulder/jonbenet-ramsey-case-former-boulder-police-chief-mark-beckner-says-police-botched-initial-handling | archive-date=December 1, 2017 | url-status=dead }}</ref> The note and a practice draft were written with a pen and pad of paper from the Ramsey home.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/12/05/us/bungled-jonbenet-case-bursts-a-city-s-majesty.html|title=Bungled JonBen\u00e9t Case Bursts a City's Majesty|date=December 5, 1997| work= [[The New York Times]] |access-date= September 13, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.nytimes.com/1997/01/09/us/report-tells-of-draft-note-for-ransom.html|title=Report Tells Of Draft Note For Ransom|date=January 9, 1997|work= The New York Times |accessdate= September 13, 2016}}</ref> According to a [[Colorado Bureau of Investigation]] report, \"There are indications that the author of the ransom note is Patricia Ramsey.\" However, the evidence fell short of a definitive conclusion.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=875&dat=19970904&id=SdQLAAAAIBAJ&sjid=M1YDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6638,205639|title=Patricia Ramsey's handwriting 'set off bells'|date=September 4, 1997| work= Today's News-Herald| publisher=Google News Archive Search|page=5|access-date=December 23, 2010|location=Denver}}</ref> Michael Baden, a board-certified [[forensic pathology|forensic pathologist]], who had consulted with both sides of the case, said he had never seen a note like it in his 60-year experience, and that he did not think it was written by an outside stranger.<ref name=\"Time Inc.\"/>\n\nA federal court ruled it highly unlikely that Patsy wrote the note, citing six certified handwriting experts. The court bemoaned the existence of self-proclaimed experts \u2013 without credentials \u2013 trying to wrangle their way into the case by accusing Patsy without scientific basis.<ref>https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/district-courts/FSupp2/253/1323/2567726/</ref>\n\n===9-1-1 call and initial search for the child===\nThe only people known to be in the house on the night of JonBen\u00e9t's death were her immediate family: Patsy and John Ramsey and their son Burke.<ref>{{cite magazine | url=http://www.people.com/article/jonbenet-ramsey-case-5-things-to-know | title=JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey Case: 5 Things to Know About the 19-Year-Old Mystery | magazine=People | date=August 2, 2016 | author=Char Adams | access-date=September 30, 2016 }}</ref> The ransom note contained specific instructions against contacting police and friends, but Patsy telephoned the police at 5:52&nbsp;a.m. [[Mountain Time Zone|MST]].<ref name=\"DC Tragic case\">{{cite news | url=http://www.dailycamera.com/ci_22446420/jonbenet-ramsey-case-history-grand-jury | title=JonBenet Ramsey's death a tragic, bizarre case from the start | author=Charlie Brennan | newspaper=Daily Camera | date=January 27, 2013 | access-date=September 29, 2016 }}</ref> She also called family and friends.<ref name=\"Maloney\">{{cite web| url= http://www.crimemagazine.com/murder-jonben%C3%A9t-ramsey| title= The Murder of JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey| last1= Maloney| first1= J. J.| last2= O'Connor| first2= J. Patrick| date= May 7, 1999| website=Crimemagazine.com| accessdate= November 19, 2014| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141129041656/http://www.crimemagazine.com/murder-jonben%C3%A9t-ramsey| archive-date= November 29, 2014| url-status= dead| df= mdy-all}}</ref> Two police officers responded to the [[9-1-1]] call and arrived at the Ramsey home within three minutes. They conducted a cursory search of the house but did not find any sign of forced entry.<ref name=\"Maloney\" />{{efn|It was later determined that some windows and a door had been left unlocked that night. In addition, a basement window was previously broken by John Ramsey when he was locked out of the house.<ref name=\"Newsweek 2016\" />\n\n[[Lou Smit]], a retired and successful homicide detective, was brought in to investigate the case. He quickly became a proponent of the intruder theory, and believed that the intruder entered through this basement window. A suitcase was found on the floor almost directly underneath this window. Smit theorized the attacker(s) planned to use this suitcase either to take JonBen\u00e9t alive as a kidnap victim or move her body out of the house, but this proved impossible.<ref name=\"DC Smit theory\">{{cite news | url=http://web.dailycamera.com/extra/ramsey/2001/01lrams.html | title=Smit presents intruder theory | author=Christopher Anderson | newspaper=Daily Camera | date=May 1, 2001 | access-date=September 29, 2016 }}</ref>}}\n\nOfficer Rick French went to the basement and came to a door that was secured by a wooden latch. He paused for a moment in front of the door, but made a critical error when he walked away without opening it. French later explained that he was looking for an exit route used by the kidnapper, which the closed inside peg ruled out. Unbeknownst to him, JonBen\u00e9t's body was on the other side of the door.<ref name=\"Newsweek 2016\">{{cite magazine | url=http://www.newsweek.com/jonbenet-ramsey-door-cops-never-opened-501705 | title=JonBen\u00e9t': The door the cops never opened | magazine=Newsweek | date=September 23, 2016 | access-date=September 28, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nJohn made arrangements to pay the ransom. A [[forensic]]s team was dispatched to the house. The team initially believed that the child had been [[kidnapping|kidnapped]], and JonBen\u00e9t's bedroom was the only room in the house that was cordoned off to prevent contamination of evidence. No precautions were taken to prevent [[Contaminated evidence|contamination of evidence]] in the rest of the house.<ref name=\"Newsweek 2016\" /> Meanwhile, friends and the family's minister arrived at the home to support the Ramseys. Victim advocates also arrived at the scene. Visitors picked up and cleaned surfaces in the kitchen, possibly destroying evidence.<ref name=\"Newsweek 2016\" /> Boulder detective Linda Arndt arrived at about 8 a.m. MST, with the goal of awaiting the kidnapper(s)' instructions, but there was never an attempt by anyone to claim the money.<ref name=Oliva />\n\n===Discovery of the body===\nAt 1:00&nbsp;p.m. MST, Detective Arndt asked John Ramsey and Fleet White, a family friend, to search the house to see if \"anything seemed amiss.\"<ref name=\"Newsweek 2016\" /> They started their search in the basement. John opened the latched door which Officer French had overlooked and found his daughter's body in one of the rooms.<ref name=\"Newsweek 2016\" /> JonBen\u00e9t's mouth was covered with [[duct tape]], a [[nylon]] cord was found around her wrists and neck, and her torso was covered by a white blanket.<ref name=\"RS\" /><ref name=Douglas /> John Ramsey picked up the child's body and took it upstairs. When JonBen\u00e9t was moved, the crime scene was further contaminated, and critical forensic evidence was disturbed for the returning forensics team.<ref name=\"Newsweek 2016\"/>{{efn|Former FBI profiler [[John E. Douglas]], who was brought in to assist the Ramseys' lawyers on the case in January 1997 to assess whether the Ramseys were involved, stated that if a family member was involved in a murder, they would generally construe events so that another person found the body. In this case, John found the body and his friend followed him into the basement room. According to Douglas, when a family member is involved in a murder, they are likely to cover their child's body in a protective manner, covering all but their head. In this case, just the torso was covered, which did not denote the kind of act a parent would generally perform. In addition, John removed the duct tape from her mouth and loosened the cord around her, which goes against the theory of \"staging\" the body. Arndt made an error when she moved JonBen\u00e9t into the living room.<ref name=Douglas>{{cite book | chapter = The JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey Murder | title=The Cases That Haunt Us: From Jack the Ripper to Jon Benet Ramsey, The FBI's Legendary Mindhunter Sheds New Light on the Mysteries That Won't Go Away | author= [[John E. Douglas]]  and Mark Olshaker | publisher=Scribner | year=2001 | isbn=0671017063  }}</ref>}}\n\nEach of the Ramseys provided handwriting, blood, and hair samples to the police. John and Patsy participated in a preliminary interview for more than two hours, and Burke was also interviewed within the first couple of weeks following JonBen\u00e9t's death.<ref name=Douglas />\n\n===Autopsy===\nThe [[autopsy]] revealed that JonBen\u00e9t had been killed by [[strangulation]] and a [[skull fracture]]. The official cause of death was \"[[asphyxia]] by strangulation associated with craniocerebral trauma.\"<ref name=\"Klaver\"/><ref name=AutopsyReport>{{cite web | url=http://hosted.ap.org/specials/interactives/_national/jonbenet_ramsey/jonbenet_ramsey_autopsy.pdf | title=Autopsy Report | date=December 27, 1996 | publisher=Office of the Boulder County Coroner | access-date=September 29, 2016 }}</ref> There was no evidence of conventional [[rape]], although [[sexual assault]] could not be ruled out. Although no [[semen]] was found, there was evidence that there had been a vaginal injury. At the time of the autopsy, the pathologist recorded that it appeared her vaginal area had been wiped with a cloth.<ref name=\"DP Evidence\">{{cite news | url=http://extras.denverpost.com/news/ram1014k.htm | title=No indictment: Evidence voluminous but tricky | author=Karen Aug\u00e9|newspaper=[[Denver Post]] | date=October 14, 1999 | access-date=September 28, 2016 }}</ref> Her death was ruled a [[homicide]].<ref name=\"Chan\">{{cite news|last=Chan|first=Melissa|title=JonBenet Ramsey: What to Know About the Beauty Queen's Murder 20 Years Later|date=September 12, 2016|access-date=September 29, 2016|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|url=http://time.com/4478185/jonbenet-ramsey-murder-20-years/}}</ref>\n\nA [[garrote]] that was made from a length of nylon cord and the broken handle of a paintbrush was tied around JonBen\u00e9t's neck and had apparently been used to strangle her. Part of the bristle end of the paintbrush was found in a tub containing Patsy's art supplies, but the bottom third of it was never found despite extensive searching of the house by the police in subsequent days.<ref name= courttv>{{cite web |url= http://www.courttv.com/onair/shows/specials/jonbenet_anatomy_of_a_cold_case.html | title= JonBen\u00e9t: Anatomy of a Cold Case |publisher=Court TV |date=  | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060709195643/http://www.courttv.com/onair/shows/specials/jonbenet_anatomy_of_a_cold_case.html | archivedate=July 9, 2006}}</ref>\n\nThe autopsy revealed a \"vegetable or fruit material which may represent [[pineapple]],\" which JonBen\u00e9t had eaten a few hours before her death.<ref name=AutopsyReport/><ref name=hickey>{{citation |editor-last= Hickey| editor-first= Eric| title= Encyclopedia of Murder and Violent Crime| edition= illustrated, reprint| publisher= SAGE| year= 2003| isbn= 9780761924371}}</ref> Photographs of the home taken on the day when JonBen\u00e9t's body was found show a bowl of pineapple on the kitchen table with a spoon in it.<ref name=hickey/> However, neither John nor Patsy said they remembered putting the bowl on the table or feeding pineapple to JonBen\u00e9t.<ref name=hickey/><ref name=interrogation/> Police reported that they found JonBen\u00e9t's nine-year-old brother Burke Ramsey's fingerprints on the bowl.<ref name=interrogation>{{cite news |title = Searching: The Interrogation Tapes|url = http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2002/10/01/48hours/main523875.shtml|publisher = 48 Hours (CBS News)|date=October 1, 2002|accessdate = July 11, 2008}}</ref> The Ramseys have always said that Burke slept through the entire night until he was awakened several hours after the police arrived.<ref name= inside />{{rp|w186\u201387}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://extras.denverpost.com/news/jon0526.htm|title=Victim's brother, 12, questioned|last=Robinson|first=Marilyn|date=May 26, 1997| work= DenverPost.com|access-date=November 19, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Blood samples===\nIn December 2003, forensic investigators extracted enough material from a mixed blood sample found on JonBen\u00e9t's underwear to establish a [[DNA]] profile.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2004/12/16/48hours/main661569.shtml |work=CBS News |title=JonBenet: DNA Rules Out Parents |date=December 16, 2004}}</ref> That DNA belonged to an unknown male person, and excluded the DNA of each of the Ramseys. The DNA was submitted to the FBI's [[Combined DNA Index System]] (CODIS), a database containing more than 1.6 million DNA profiles, but the sample did not match any profile in the database.<ref name=\"DC Brennan\" /> In October 2016, a report said that new forensic analysis with more sensitive techniques revealed that the original DNA contained genetic markers from two individuals other than JonBen\u00e9t.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-crime-jonbenet-idUSKCN12T007 |work=Reuters |title=DNA cited to clear JonBenet Ramsey family in murder in question: report |date=October 28, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailycamera.com/news/jonbenet-ramsey/ci_30514220/jonbenet-ramsey-dna-evidence |work=Daily Camera |title=DNA in doubt: New analysis challenges DA's exoneration of Ramseys |date=October 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\nA. James Kolar, who was a lead investigator for the D.A.'s office, said that there were additional traces of male DNA found on the cord and paintbrush that Boulder district attorney Mary Lacy did not mention, and that there were six separate DNA samples belonging to unknown individuals that were found by the test.<ref name=\"Time Inc.\"/> Former FBI profiler Candice Delong believes that the DNA, having shown up identically in several different places on multiple surfaces, belongs to the killer.<ref>https://www.denverpost.com/2016/09/19/burke-ramsey-hopes-jonbenet-murder-investigation-finds-killer/</ref> Former Adams County, Colorado, District Attorney Bob Grant, who has assisted the Boulder DA's office on the case for many years, also believes that the DNA evidence is significant, saying that any resolution of the case would have to explain how the DNA showed up on several pieces of JonBen\u00e9t's clothing.<ref>http://www.dailycamera.com/ci_30317043/boulder-police-chief-updates-jonbenet-ramsey-case-20</ref> Forensic pathologist Michael Baden said, \"Trace amounts of DNA can get on places and clothing from all different, nonsuspicious means. There is no forensic evidence to show that this is a stranger murder.\"<ref name=\"Time Inc.\"/>\n\n==Investigation==\nExperts, media commentators, and the Ramseys have identified potential suspects in the case.<ref name=\"CBS DNA Rules\" /> Boulder police initially focused almost exclusively upon John and Patsy,<ref name=\"CBS DNA Rules\" /> but by October 1997 had over 1,600 people in their index of [[person of interest|persons of interest]] for the case.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://web.dailycamera.com/extra/ramsey/1997/10/24-1.html | title=Police cast wide net in Ramsey investigation | author=Alli Krupski | newspaper=Daily Camera|date=October 24, 1997 | accessdate=October 1, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nErrors that were made in the initial investigation complicated the resolution of the investigation and applicable theory. Those errors included loss and contamination of evidence, lack of experienced and technical staff on the investigation, evidence shared with the Ramseys, and delayed informal interviews with the parents.<ref name=\"Newsweek 2016\" /><ref name=\"NYT Bungled\" />{{efn|A Boulder defense attorney, Lee Hill, commented that: \"The public feels that the police have coddled the Ramseys because they are rich and influential in Boulder.\"<ref name=\"NYT Bungled\" />}}\n\n[[Lou Smit]] was a detective who came out of retirement in early 1997 to assist the Boulder County [[District Attorney]]'s office with the case. In May 1998, he presented his findings to the Boulder police with other staff members of the DA's Office, concluding that the evidence pointed away from the Ramseys. They were unable to successfully challenge the police department's belief that the Ramseys were guilty. The DA's office sought to take control of the investigation.<ref name=\"KoJB\">{{cite AV media | title=The Killing of JonBen\u00e9t: The Truth Uncovered | publisher=Mills Productions for [[A&E (TV network)|A&E]] network| people=David Mills and Janet Taylor, executive producers for Mill Productions |medium=television | date=September 5, 2016 }}</ref> Due to the animosity between the police and the DA's office, and the pressure to obtain a conviction, [[Governor of Colorado|Colorado governor]] [[Roy Romer]] interceded and named Michael Kane as [[special prosecutor]] to initiate a [[grand jury]].<ref name=\"NW No Justice\">{{cite news | url=http://www.newsweek.com/no-justice-jonbenet-168028 | title=No Justice for JonBenet | work=[[Newsweek]] | date=October 24, 1999 | accessdate=September 30, 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://articles.philly.com/1998-08-11/news/25727328_1_special-prosecutor-roy-romer-district-attorney-alex-hunter | title=Special Prosecutor For Ramsey Case? Colorado's Governor Will Meet With Four Area District Attorneys To Decide Whether To Appoint One | date=August 11, 1998 | author=Gwen Florio | newspaper=The Philadelphia Inquirer | publisher=philly.com | access-date=September 30, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nTwo of the lead investigators in the case had opposing views. Both Lou Smit and Steve Thomas ultimately resigned {{ndash}} Smit because he believed that the investigation had incompetently overlooked the intruder hypothesis,<ref name=\"NW No Justice\" /> and Thomas because the DA's office had interfered with and failed to support the police investigation of the case.<ref name=\"Klaver\"/><ref name=inside/><ref name= courttv /><ref name=ThomasResignation>{{cite news |first=Steve |last=Thomas | url=http://web.dailycamera.com/extra/ramsey/1998/07thomle.html | title=The Thomas resignation letter | date=August 6, 1998| newspaper=Daily Camera }}</ref>\n\nA grand jury was convened beginning September 15, 1998 to consider [[indictment|indicting]] the Ramseys for charges relating to the case.<ref name=\"HP Timeline\">{{cite news | url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/01/28/jonbenet-ramsey-case-time_n_2561598.html | title=JonBenet Ramsey Case Timeline: 1996\u20132012 | date=January 27, 2013 |  author=<!-- Daily Camera staff --> | work=Huffington Post | accessdate=September 29, 2016 }}</ref><ref name=Garnett /> In 1999, the grand jury returned a [[true bill]] to charge the Ramseys with placing the child at risk in a way that led to her death and with [[obstruction of justice|obstructing an investigation of murder]], based on the [[probable cause]] standard applied in such grand jury proceedings. But [[Boulder County, Colorado|Boulder County]] District Attorney Alex Hunter did not prosecute them, because he did not believe that he could meet the higher standard of proving guilt [[beyond a reasonable doubt]] that is required for a criminal conviction.<ref name=Garnett />\n\nMary Lacy, the next Boulder County District Attorney, took over the investigation from the police on December 26, 2002. In April 2003, she agreed with a federal judge who sat on a 2002 [[libel]] case that evidence in the suit is \"more consistent with a theory that an intruder murdered JonBen\u00e9t than it was with a theory that Mrs. Ramsey did\".<ref name=\"HP Timeline\" /> On July 9, 2008, the Boulder District Attorney's office announced that, as a result of newly developed DNA sampling and testing techniques ([[touch DNA]] analysis), the Ramsey family members were excluded as suspects in the case. Lacy publicly exonerated the Ramseys.<ref name=ramseyspressrelease>{{cite news|title=Ramsey Press Release |last=Lacy |first=Mary T. |publisher=District Attorney's Office, Twentieth Judicial District, Boulder, Colorado |date=July 9, 2008 |url=http://www.bouldercounty.org/newsroom/templates/?a=1256&z=13 |access-date=July 9, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080801081500/http://www.bouldercounty.org/newsroom/templates/?a=1256&z=13 |archivedate=August 1, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/25608543/ns/us_news-crime_and_courts/t/family-cleared-jonbenet-ramseys-death/|title=Family cleared in JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey's death|date=July 9, 2008| website=NBCNews.com| access-date= November 19, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn February 2, 2009, Boulder police chief Mark Beckner announced that Stan Garnett, the new Boulder County District Attorney, was turning the case over to his agency, and that his team would resume investigating it.<ref name=bonus/> Garnett found that the [[statute of limitations]] for the crimes identified in the 1999 grand jury true bill had expired, and did not pursue review of the case against the Ramseys.<ref name=Garnett>{{cite web |last= Garnett| first= Stan| title= Boulder DA Stan Garnett: Another perspective on release of Ramsey indictment|url=http://www.dailycamera.com/guest-opinions/ci_24389428/stan-garnett-boulder-district-attorney-jonbenet-ramsey-case|website= Daily Camera}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2010, the Boulder police reopened the cold case. New interviews were conducted following a fresh inquiry by a committee that included state and federal investigators. Police were expected to use the latest [[DNA]] technology in their investigation.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/northamerica/usa/8044818/JonBenet-Ramsey-murder-case-reopened.html |location=London |work=The Daily Telegraph |first=Nick |last=Allen |title=JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey murder case reopened |date=October 5, 2010}}</ref> There was no new information gleaned from those interviews.<ref name=\"HP Kolar\">{{cite news | url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/07/18/jonbenet-ramsey-case-jame_n_1687905.html | title=JonBenet Ramsey Case: James Kolar, Former Leading Investigator Rejects Intruder Theory In New Book | date=July 20, 2012 | work=Huffington Post | access-date=September 30, 2016 }}</ref> It was reported in September 2016 that the investigation into JonBen\u00e9t's death continues to be an active homicide case, per Boulder Police Chief Greg Testa.<ref name=\"DC Brennan\">{{cite news | url=http://www.dailycamera.com/news/boulder/ci_30317043/boulder-police-chief-updates-jonbenet-ramsey-case-20 | title=Boulder police chief updates JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey case, 20 years on | author=Charlie Brennan | newspaper=[[Daily Camera]] | date=September 1, 2016 | access-date=September 26, 2016 }}</ref>{{efn|Boulder Police Chief Greg Testa stated in September 2016 that \"To date, the Boulder Police Department has processed more than 1,500 pieces of evidence, including the analysis of over 200 DNA samples. [...] Our major crimes unit has received and reviewed or investigated over 20,000 tips, letters or emails. Our detectives have traveled to over 18 states and interviewed or spoken with more than 1,000 individuals.\"<ref name=\"DC Brennan\" />}}\n\nIn 2015, Beckner disagreed with exonerating the Ramseys, stating, \"Exonerating anyone based on a small piece of evidence that has not yet been proved to even be connected to the crime is absurd.\"<ref name=\"Time Inc.\"/> He also stated that the unknown DNA from JonBenet's clothing \"has got to be the focus of the investigation\" at this point in time and that, until one can prove otherwise, \"the suspect is the donator [sic] of that unknown DNA.\"<ref>http://www.dailycamera.com/ci_27591666/mark-beckner-opens-up-about-jonbenet-ramsey-case</ref>  In 2016, Gordon Coombes, a former investigator for the Boulder County District Attorney's office, also questioned total absolution of the Ramseys, stating, \"We all shed DNA all the time within our skin cells. It can be deposited anywhere at any time for various reasons, reasons that are benign. To clear somebody just on the premise of touch DNA, especially when you have a situation where the crime scene wasn't secure at the beginning ... really is a stretch.\"<ref name=\"NYP Morabito\" /> Steven E. Pitt, a [[forensic psychiatrist]] hired by Boulder authorities, said, \"Lacy's public exoneration of the Ramseys was a big slap in the face to Chief Beckner and the core group of detectives who had been working on the case for years.\"<ref name=\"Time Inc.\"/>\n\n==Theories and suspects==\n===Family member theory===\nThere are two types of theories about the death of JonBen\u00e9t. One is the family member theory.<ref name=\"NYP Morabito\"/> Boulder police initially concentrated almost exclusively upon the parents, John and Patsy Ramsey.<ref name=\"CBS DNA Rules\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/jonbenet-dna-rules-out-parents/#comments |title=JonBenet: DNA Rules Out Parents |date=December 16, 2004 |website=CBSNews.com |accessdate=November 19, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160115025353/http://www.cbsnews.com/news/jonbenet-dna-rules-out-parents/ |archivedate=January 15, 2016 }}</ref><ref name=\"NYT Bungled\">{{ cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/12/05/us/bungled-jonbenet-case-bursts-a-city-s-majesty.html?_r=0 | title=Bungled JonBen\u00e9t Case Bursts a City's Majesty | author=James Brooke | date=December 5, 1997 | newspaper=The New York Times | access-date=September 28, 2016 }}</ref> According to [[Gregg McCrary]], a retired profiler with the FBI, \"statistically, it is a 12-to-1 probability that it's a family member or a care giver\" who is involved in the homicide of a child.<ref name=\"NYT Bungled\" />  The FBI has stated that there was the practiced note on the note pad that John Ramsey had given earlier that day and that the parents were involved. The police saw no evidence of a forced entry, but they did see evidence of staging of the scene, such as the ransom note. They did not find the Ramseys cooperative in helping them solve the death of their daughter.<ref name=\"NYT Bungled\" />{{efn|James Brooke of ''The New York Times'' reported, \n<blockquote>\"The Ramseys have consistently maintained their innocence. But for four months after the murder, they declined to talk to the police. Instead, they mounted a defense team that sounds like a defense lawyer's Christmas carol: eight lawyers, four publicists, three private investigators, two handwriting analysts and one retired F.B.I. profiler.\"<ref name=\"NYT Bungled\" />|name=Decline}} The Ramseys had said that their reluctance was due to their fear that there would not be a full investigation for intruders and that they would be hastily selected as the key suspects in the case, according to the ''Daily Camera''.<ref name=\"DC Tragic case\" />\n\nOne theory is that Patsy struck JonBen\u00e9t in a fit of rage after a bedwetting episode, and strangled her to cover up what had happened, after mistakenly thinking she was already dead.<ref name=\"DC Tragic case\"/><ref name=\"BC Dr Phil\" /> But Patsy did not have a known history of uncontrolled anger.<ref name=\"BC Dr Phil\" /> JonBen\u00e9t's brother later said, \"We didn't get spanked, nothing of the sort, nothing close, nothing near laying a finger on us, let alone killing your child.\"<ref name=\"BC Dr Phil\" />\n\nTheoretically, the strangulation could have been a \"[[red herring]]\" aspect to conceal other elements of the assault and killing.<ref name=\"KoJB\" /><ref name=\"BC Dr Phil\">{{cite news |url=http://www.dailycamera.com/news/boulder/ci_30359976/burke-ramsey-interview-dr-phil-jonbenet-boulder | title=Burke Ramsey responds to conspiracy theories, accusations about JonBen\u00e9t's murder | author=<!-- Denver Post staff --> | newspaper=Daily Camera | date=September 14, 2016 | access-date=September 26, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nBurke, who was nine years old at the time of JonBen\u00e9t's death, was interviewed by investigators at least three times.<ref name=\"DC Burke attny in town\" /> The first two interviews did not raise any concerns about him. A review by a child psychologist stated that it appeared that the Ramseys had \"healthy, caring family relationships\".<ref name=\"KoJB\" /> In 1998, Boulder Police Chief Mark Beckner said during an interview with a news reporter that Burke Ramsey was not involved in the killing of his sister. In May 1999, the Boulder County District Attorney's office reiterated that Burke Ramsey was not a suspect.<ref name=\"DC Not Burke\">{{cite news | url=http://web.dailycamera.com/extra/ramsey/1999/21arams.html | title=Burke Ramsey not suspect in killing, DA's office says | author=Christopher Anderson | newspaper=Daily Camera | date=May 1999 | access-date=October 1, 2016 }}</ref> The investigators had never considered him a suspect.<ref name=\"DC Burke gj\">{{cite news | url=http://web.dailycamera.com/extra/ramsey/1999/52699crams.html | title=Grand Jury heard from JonBen\u00e9t's brother| author=<!-- Camera staff and wire services -->|date=May 26, 1999 | access-date=October 1, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nThe Ramseys offered a $100,000 reward in a newspaper ad dated April 27, 1997.<ref name=\"HP Timeline\" /> Three days later, more than four months after the body of their daughter was found, they submitted for the first time to separate formal interviews at the Boulder County Justice Center.<ref name=\"HP Timeline\" />\n\nIn 1999, Colorado Governor [[Bill Owens (Colorado politician)|Bill Owens]] spoke out, telling the Ramsey couple to \"quit hiding behind their attorneys, quit hiding behind their [[public relations|PR]] firm\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/5260914.stm |title=Warning on JonBen\u00e9t speculation |work=BBC News |date=August 17, 2006 |access-date=June 22, 2011}}</ref>{{efn|name=Decline}}\n\nA Colorado [[grand jury]] voted in 1999 to indict the parents.<ref name=Martinez />{{efn|Burke testified at a 1999 grand jury hearing.<ref name=\"DC Burke gj\" /> Burke Ramsey's attorney, Jim Jenkins, sought to prevent his testifying at the grand jury and to eliminate him as a suspect,<ref name=\"DC Burke attny in town\">{{cite news |url=http://web.dailycamera.com/extra/ramsey/1999/20crmsy.html |title=Burke Ramsey's attorney in town: Brother of slain girl could be asked to give grand jury more information |newspaper= Daily Camera |date=May 20, 1999 |access-date=September 29, 2016}}</ref> but the DA's office said that Burke was not and never had been a suspect.<ref name=\"DC Not Burke\" /><ref name=\"DC Burke gj\" />}} The indictment cited \"two counts each of child abuse\" and said the parents \"did unlawfully, knowingly, recklessly and feloniously permit a child to be unreasonably placed in a situation that posed a threat of injury to the child's life or health, which resulted in the death of JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey, a child under the age of sixteen.\"<ref name=\"DP Indictment\">{{cite news | url=http://www.denverpost.com/2013/10/25/jonbent-ramsey-grand-jury-indictment-accused-parents-of-child-abuse-resulting-in-death/ | title=JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey grand jury indictment accused parents of child abuse resulting in death | newspaper=[[Denver Post]] | date=October 25, 2013 | access-date=September 26, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nAmong the experts who testified in the case were DNA specialist [[Barry Scheck]] and forensic expert [[Henry Lee (forensic scientist)|Dr. Henry Lee]].<ref name=\"HP Timeline\" /> On October 13, 1999, Alex Hunter, who was the district attorney at the time, refused to sign the indictment, saying that the evidence was insufficient for prosecution.<ref name=\"HP Timeline\" /><ref name=Martinez>{{cite news |first1=Michael |last1=Martinez |first2= Faith |last2= Karimi |url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/10/25/justice/jonbenet-ramsey-documents/ |title=Papers: Grand jury in 1999 sought to indict JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey's parents |publisher=CNN |date=October 25, 2013 |access-date=September 5, 2015}}</ref> The public thought that the grand jury investigation had been inconclusive.<ref>{{cite web |title=JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey grand jury voted to indict parents in 1999, but the District Attorney refused to prosecute| first= Charlie| last= Brennan| date= January 27, 2013| url=http://www.dailycamera.com/news/boulder/ci_22446410/boulder-grand-jury-voted-indict-ramseys|website= The Daily Camera|access-date=January 28, 2013}}</ref> In 2002, the statute of limitations on the grand jury's charges expired.<ref name=\"DP Indictment\" />\n\nThe grand jury's vote to indict was not revealed publicly until October 25, 2013, when previously sealed court documents were released.{{efn|In September 2013, ''[[Daily Camera]]'' reporter Charlie Brennan and the Reporters Committee for Freedom of the Press filed a lawsuit to press DA Stan Garnett to release the grand jury's indictment.<ref>{{cite news |last=Byars|first=Mitchell|title=Camera reporter sues Boulder DA seeking release of Ramsey indictment|url=http://www.dailycamera.com/news/boulder/ci_24124759/camera-reporter-sues-boulder-da-seeking-release-ramsey|newspaper=Boulder Daily Camera|date=September 18, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe police sought to interview Burke Ramsey again in September 2010, according to [[L. Lin Wood]], a high-profile [[libel]] (defamation) attorney whom the Ramsey family hired in 1999.<ref name=\"NW No Justice\"/><ref name=\"HP Timeline\" /> In 2012, the book ''Foreign Faction \u2013 Who Really Kidnapped JonBenet?'' by A. James Kolar, a former investigator under Boulder County District Attorney Lacy, was published. The book discounts the intruder theory and proposes scenarios of Ramsey family involvement in JonBen\u00e9t's death.<ref name=\"HP Timeline\" />\n\nIn mid-October 2013, a judge ruled that the DA must show why the indictment should remain sealed.<ref>{{cite web |last=Byars|first=Mitchell|title=Judge orders Boulder DA to show why Ramsey indictment should remain secret|url=http://www.dailycamera.com/news/boulder/ci_24331072/judge-orders-boulder-da-show-why-ramsey-indictment|website= Daily Camera}}</ref> ''[[The Denver Post]]'' (a sister paper of the ''Daily Camera'') published an editorial calling for the indictment to be unsealed.<ref>{{cite news|title=Editorial: Time to unseal indictment in JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey case |url=http://www.denverpost.com/ci_24354220/editorial-time-unseal-indictment-jonben-t-ramsey-case |newspaper=Denver Post |date=October 21, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131023061640/http://www.denverpost.com/ci_24354220/editorial-time-unseal-indictment-jonben-t-ramsey-case |archivedate=October 23, 2013 }}</ref>}}\n\n''[[The Case of: JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey]]'', a show broadcast on [[CBS]] on September 18 and 19, 2016, said that they used a group of experts to evaluate the evidence. The group theorized that Burke hit his sister in the head with a heavy object, perhaps not intending to kill her. They suggested that the ransom letter was an attempt to cover up the circumstances of JonBenet's death.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbs.com/shows/the-case-of-jonbenet-ramsey/|title=The Case of JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey|publisher=CBS|access-date=September 29, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160928102130/http://www.cbs.com/shows/the-case-of-jonbenet-ramsey/|archivedate=September 28, 2016}}</ref> On behalf of Burke Ramsey, his counsel Wood filed defamation lawsuits against CBS, the producers of the program, and several of its participants, based on many of its claims.<ref>[https://people.com/crime/burke-ramsey-jonbenet-cbs-series-lawsuit/ \"Burke Ramsey- JonBenet/ CBS series lawsuit\"], ''People'' magazine</ref>\n\n===Intruder theory===\nThe second theory is the intruder theory. The Ramseys developed a relationship with District Attorney Mary Lacy and her office, which was criticized by authorities such as the city's mayor, Leslie L Durgin.<ref name=\"NYP Morabito\"/><ref name=\"NYT Bungled\" />{{efn|The city's mayor Leslie L Durgin said, \"I'm extremely concerned about the relationship between the district attorney's office and the Ramsey attorneys. The perception is that they are closer than we thought.\" Ann Louise Bardach, ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'' journalist, wrote that there were weekly breakfast meetings between a Ramsey defense lawyer and Peter Hofstrom, the prosecutor's liaison to the Ramsey family.<ref name=\"NYT Bungled\" />}} Although the police may have still suspected the Ramseys, they and the prosecutors followed leads for intruders partly due to the unidentified boot mark left in the basement room where JonBen\u00e9t's body was found.<ref name=\"Newsweek 2016\"/> The police routinely ignored leads to any suspects outside of the family.<ref>https://www.cbsnews.com/news/jonbenet-dna-rules-out-parents/</ref>\n\nEarly suspects included neighbor Bill McReynolds, who played Santa Claus; former family housekeeper Linda Hoffmann-Pugh, and a man named Michael Helgoth, who died in an apparent [[suicide]] shortly after JonBen\u00e9t's death. Hundreds of DNA tests were performed to find a match to the DNA recovered during her autopsy.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/real-life/true-stories/santa-and-the-housekeeper-the-forgotten-jonbenet-suspects/news-story/c921605802d5086911a1a34780225a4d | title=Santa and the housekeeper: The forgotten JonBenet suspects | publisher=news.com.au | date=September 23, 2016 | access-date=September 29, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nSmit assessed the evidence and concluded that an intruder had committed the crime.<ref name=taha>{{cite news| last= Taha| first= Nadia | url= https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/14/us/14smit.html | title= Lou Smit, Detective in JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey Case, Is Dead at 75| work= [[The New York Times]]| date= August 13, 2010| access-date= August 14, 2010}}</ref> On the night JonBen\u00e9t was killed, there had been two windows that were left slightly open to allow for electrical cords for the outside Christmas lights to pass through, a broken basement window, and one unlocked door.<ref name=\"Maloney\" />{{efn|It was later determined that some windows and a door had been left unlocked that night. In addition, a basement window was previously broken by John Ramsey when he was locked out of the house.<ref name=\"Newsweek 2016\" />\n\n[[Lou Smit]], a retired and successful homicide detective, was brought in to investigate the case. He quickly became a proponent of the intruder theory, and believed that the intruder entered through this basement window. A suitcase was found on the floor almost directly underneath this window. Smit theorized the attacker(s) planned to use this suitcase either to take JonBen\u00e9t alive as a kidnap victim or move her body out of the house, but this proved impossible.<ref name=\"DC Smit theory\">{{cite news | url=http://web.dailycamera.com/extra/ramsey/2001/01lrams.html | title=Smit presents intruder theory | author=Christopher Anderson | newspaper=Daily Camera | date=May 1, 2001 | access-date=September 29, 2016 }}</ref>}} Smit's theory was that someone entered the Ramsey home through the broken basement window. This has been criticized because there was an intact cobweb in the basement window.<ref name=\"Time Inc.\"/> The steel grate that covered the window also had undisturbed cobwebs, and the foliage around the grate had been undisturbed.<ref name=\"Thomas and Davis\">{{cite book|vauthors=Thomas S, Davis DA|title =JonBenet: Inside the Ramsey Murder Investigation|isbn = 1429981733|publisher=[[St. Martin's Press]]|year=2011|pages=40, 48|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pC3k1vnwLhEC&pg=PA40&lpg=PA40}}</ref> There were also cobwebs in the tracks of various windows, and dust and debris were on some sills.<ref name=\"Thomas and Davis\"/> Smit believed that the intruder subdued JonBen\u00e9t using a stun gun and took her down to the basement. JonBen\u00e9t was killed and a ransom note was left.<ref name=\"RS\">{{cite news | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/news/3-big-ways-the-case-of-jonbenet-ramsey-got-it-wrong-w440970 | title=3 Big Ways 'The Case of: JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey' Got It Wrong | work=Rolling Stone | date=September 20, 2016 | author=Amelia McDonell-Parry | access-date=September 26, 2016 }}</ref> Smit's theory was supported by former FBI agent [[John E. Douglas]], who had been hired by the Ramsey family.<ref name=taha/>{{efn|In his book ''The Cases That Haunt Us'', former FBI agent [[John E. Douglas]] (hired by the Ramsey family) writes that he quibbled with a few of Smit's interpretations but generally agreed with his investigation and conclusions. Douglas particularly praised Smit's discovery in autopsy photos of what appeared to be previously overlooked evidence of a \"[[electroshock weapon|stun gun]]\" having been used to subdue JonBen\u00e9t.<ref name=taha/>}}  Believing that the Ramseys were innocent, Smit resigned from the investigation on September 20, 1998, five days after the grand jury was convened against the Ramseys.<ref name=\"HP Timeline\" /> While no longer an official investigator on the case, Smit continued to work on it until his death in 2010.<ref name=taha/>\n\nStephen Singular, author of the book ''Presumed Guilty: An Investigation into the JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey Case, the Media and the Culture of Pornography'' (2016), refers to consultations with cyber-crime specialists who believe that JonBen\u00e9t, due to her beauty pageant experience, could have attracted the attention of [[Child pornography|child pornographers]] and [[Pedophilia|pedophiles]].<ref>{{citation |title= The Pornography Connection |first= Patrick |last= Bellamy}}</ref>\n\nIt was determined that there had been more than 100 burglaries in the Ramseys' neighborhood in the months before JonBen\u00e9t's murder. There were 38 registered [[sex offender]]s living within a two-mile (3&nbsp;km) radius of the Ramseys' home.<ref name= CBSLeung2004>{{cite web|last1=Leung|first1=Rebecca|title=JonBenet: DNA Rules Out Parents| url= http://www.cbsnews.com/news/jonbenet-dna-rules-out-parents/|website=CBS News|access-date=August 10, 2016| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160115025353/http://www.cbsnews.com/news/jonbenet-dna-rules-out-parents/|archivedate=January 15, 2016| date= December 16, 2004}}</ref> In 2001, former Boulder County prosecutor Trip DeMuth and Boulder County Sheriff's Detective Steve Ainsworth stated that there should be a more aggressive investigation of the intruder theory.<ref name=\"DC Smit theory\"/>\n\nOne of the individuals whom Smit identified as a suspect was Gary Howard Oliva, who was arrested for \"two counts of attempted sexual exploitation of a child and one count of sexual exploitation of a child\" charges in June 2016, according to Boulder's ''[[Daily Camera]]''. Oliva, a registered sex offender, was publicly identified as a suspect in an October 2002 episode of ''[[48 Hours (TV series)|48 Hours Investigates]]''.<ref name=Oliva>{{cite news | url=http://www.dailycamera.com/news/boulder/ci_30041518/jonbenet-ramsey-murder-suspect-gary-oliva-charged-boulder-child-porn-case | title=Ramsey murder suspect charged in Boulder child porn case | author=Charlie Brennan | date=June 21, 2016 | access-date=September 28, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n''The Killing of JonBen\u00e9t: The Truth Uncovered'', broadcast by [[A&E (TV network)|A&E]] on September 5, 2016, concluded that an unidentified male was responsible for JonBen\u00e9t's death, based on forensic DNA analysis of evidence. In the documentary, Dr. Lawrence Kobilinsky stated that \"an unidentified male committed this crime\".<ref>{{ cite news | url=http://www.thedenverchannel.com/news/front-range/boulder/new-details-revealed-about-jonbenet-ramseys-murder-in-ae-documentary | title=New details revealed about JonBenet Ramsey's murder in A&E documentary | author=Jennifer Kovaleski | date=September 6, 2016 | access-date= September 30, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nThe District Attorney's office investigating pedophiles indicated to former Denver prosecutor Craig Silverman that the District Attorney's office followed the intruder theory. Silverman said, \"Once you have conceded the possibility of an intruder, I don't see how any Ramsey could ever be successfully prosecuted.\"<ref name=\"NYT Bungled\" /> Gordon Coombes joined the office as an investigator under Lacy when they were testing JonBen\u00e9t's clothing for touch DNA. He also said that Lacy strongly supported the intruder theory and talked about it with the staff. Although he was not directly involved with the case, he said he was told not to voice opposition to the theory because he might lose his job. \"It just seemed weird the whole premise of ... this attempt to influence the entire agency,\" he stated.<ref name=\"NYP Morabito\" />\n\n==False confession==\nJohn Mark Karr, a 41-year-old elementary school teacher, was arrested in [[Bangkok]], [[Thailand]], on August 15, 2006 when he [[false confession|falsely confessed]] to murdering JonBen\u00e9t.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Ferguson |first=Zoe |title=Where Is John Mark Karr, The Man Who Falsely Confessed to JonBenet Ramsey's Murder, & What Is He Doing Now? |url=https://www.bustle.com/articles/72098-where-is-john-mark-karr-the-man-who-falsely-confessed-to-jonbenet-ramseys-murder-what |date=26 March 2015 |access-date=1 July 2017 |magazine=[[Bustle (magazine)|Bustle]]}}</ref> He claimed that he had drugged, sexually assaulted, and accidentally killed her.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/14379566/ns/us_news-crime_and_courts/t/suspect-jonbenet-ramseys-death-accident/|title=Suspect: JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey's death 'an accident'|date=August 17, 2006|website=NBCNews.com|accessdate=November 19, 2014}}</ref>  According to [[CNN]], \"Authorities also said they did not find any evidence linking [Karr] to the crime scene.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2006/LAW/10/16/karr.interview/ |work=CNN |title=Karr: 'I've never harmed a child'}}</ref><ref name=\"CNN Karr\" />\n\nIn his confession, Karr had provided only basic facts that were publicly known and failed to provide any convincing details. His claim that he had drugged JonBen\u00e9t was doubted because the autopsy indicated that no drugs were found in her body.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.denverpost.com/news/ci_4190797 |title=Experts incredulous over JonBen\u00e9t confession |last1=Martin |first1=Claire |last2=Simpson |first2=Kevin |date=August 17, 2006 |website=DenverPost.com |access-date=November 19, 2014}}</ref> DNA samples that were taken from Karr did not match DNA found on JonBen\u00e9t's body.<ref name=\"CNN Karr\">{{cite news |url= http://www.cnn.com/2006/LAW/08/28/ramsey.arrest/index.html |title=No DNA match, no JonBen\u00e9t charges |website=CNN.com |date=August 28, 2006|access-date=June 22, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.findlaw.com/hdocs/docs/karr/cokarr82806mq.html |title=Not the source of the DNA found |website=Findlaw.com |date=August 22, 2006 |access-date=June 22, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.findlaw.com/hdocs/docs/karr/cokarr82806mq.html |title=D.A.'s Motion to Quash Arrest Warrant |website= Findlaw.com |date=August 22, 2006|access-date=June 22, 2011}}</ref>{{efn|Authorities had tracked Karr down by using the [[Internet]] after [[email]]s were sent regarding the case to [[Michael Tracey]], a journalism professor at the [[University of Colorado at Boulder|University of Colorado]].<ref>{{cite web|date=August 17, 2006 |url=http://www.crimelibrary.com/news/original/0806/1703_ramsey_arrest_john_karr.html |title=No Forensic Evidence Currently Links John Karr to JonBen\u00e9t Murder |publisher=Crime Library |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060901231718/http://www.crimelibrary.com/news/original/0806/1703_ramsey_arrest_john_karr.html |archivedate=September 1, 2006 }}</ref> After Karr was arrested and brought back to the US, he was released to face extradition for [[child pornography]] charges that originated in [[Sonoma County, California]]. These charges against him were subsequently dismissed<ref name=\"CNN Karr\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,1543277,00.html|title=John Mark Karr's Child Porn Case Dismissed|date=October 5, 2006|website=People.com|access-date=November 19, 2014}}</ref> due to lack of evidence.<ref name=\"HP Timeline\" /> While he was under investigation, the press coverage of Karr's false confession was described as a [[media frenzy]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/nation/2006-08-18-ramsey-thailand_x.htm|title=JonBen\u00e9t slaying suspect returning to U.S., media frenzy|website=USAToday.com|access-date=September 16, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/world/archives/2006/08/30/2003325488|title=Media frenzy over Karr shows nothing's changed|website=Taipeitimes.com |access-date=September 16, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.editorandpublisher.com/PrintArticle/Karr-Cleared-in-JonBenet-Case-After-Media-Frenzy |title= Karr Cleared in JonBen\u00e9t Case - After Media Frenzy |website=Editorandpublisher.com |date=August 28, 2006|access-date=June 9, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2006-09-07/news/0609070022_1_john-mark-karr-wilson-story-joseph-wilson |work=Chicago Tribune |first=Jonah |last=Goldberg |title=Media frenzy, facts collide |date=September 7, 2006}}</ref>}}\n\n==Defamation lawsuits==\nLin Wood, the Ramseys' family libel attorney, filed [[defamation]] lawsuits against several people and companies that had reported on the case, starting in 1999.  They sued ''[[Star (magazine)|Star]]'' magazine and its parent company [[American Media (publisher)|American Media, Inc.]] on their son's behalf in 1999.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://web.dailycamera.com/extra/ramsey/1999/01crams.html | title=Ramseys sue Star on behalf of son: Libel suit seeks $25 million in damages against tabloid | author=Shelley Hill | newspaper=Daily Camera | location=Boulder, Colorado | date=December 1, 1999 | access-date=October 11, 2016 }}</ref> Defamation suits have been filed by the Ramseys and their friends against several unnamed media outlets.<ref>{{ cite news | url=http://fox6now.com/2015/02/25/jonbenet-ramsey-murder-case-former-police-chief-opens-up-on-reddit-and-now-apparently-regrets-remarks/ | title=JonBenet Ramsey murder case: Former police chief opens up on Reddit, and now apparently regrets remarks | publisher=Fox6 Now | date=February 25, 2015 | access-date=October 11, 2016 }}</ref> A defamation suit was filed in 2001 against the authors and publisher of ''JonBen\u00e9t: Inside the Ramsey Murder Investigation'' (2000). The suit against Don Davis, Steven Thomas, and [[St. Martin's Press]] was settled out of court the following year.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.thedenverchannel.com/news/ramseys-settle-book-libel-suit | title=Ramseys Settle Book Libel Suit: Former Boulder Detective Settles Case Out Of Court | date=March 20, 2002 | publisher=7NEWS & TheDenverChannel.com | access-date=October 11, 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171011022521/http://www.thedenverchannel.com/news/ramseys-settle-book-libel-suit | archive-date=October 11, 2017 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nJohn and Patsy Ramsey were sued in two defamation lawsuits arising from the publication of their book, ''The Death of Innocence'' (2001). These suits were brought by two persons named in the book who were said to have been investigated by Boulder police as suspects in the case. The Ramseys were defended in those lawsuits by Lin Wood and three other Atlanta attorneys, James C. Rawls, Eric P. Schroeder, and S. Derek Bauer. They obtained the dismissal of both lawsuits.  U.S. District Court Judge Julie Carnes later concluded that \"abundant evidence\" in the murder case pointed to an intruder having committed the crime.<ref>{{cite web |first= R. Robin |last= McDonald |url=http://www.law.com/jsp/nlj/PubArticleNLJ.jsp?id=1202429072171&slreturn=1&hbxlogin=1 |title= Northern District of Georgia's New Chief Judge Reflects on Her Career |website=Law.com |date=March 16, 2009| access-date= June 22, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2006, Rod Westmoreland, a friend of John Ramsey, filed a defamation suit against an anonymous web surfer who had posted two messages on Internet forums using the pseudonym \"undertheradar\" implicating Westmoreland in the murder.<ref>{{cite web |author= Time Waster |url=http://www.thesmokinggun.com/archive/1109061jonbenet1.html |title=Man Sues Over JonBen\u00e9t Murder Claim |website=Thesmokinggun.com |date=November 9, 2006|access-date=June 22, 2011}}</ref>\n\nDuring a September 2016 interview with [[WWJ-TV|CBS Detroit]] and in ''[[The Case of: JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey]]'' documentary television program, forensic pathologist [[Dr. Werner Spitz]] accused Burke Ramsey of killing his sister.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://time.com/4522966/jonbenet-ramsey-brother-sues/|title=JonBenet Ramsey's Brother Files $150 Million Defamation Suit|last=Chan|first=Melissa|website=TIME.com|access-date=October 8, 2016}}</ref> On October 6, 2016, Burke filed a defamation lawsuit against Spitz. Burke and his attorneys, who include Lin Wood, sought a total of $150 million in punitive and compensatory damages. Wood said he would also file a suit against CBS at the end of October 2016.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://denver.cbslocal.com/2016/10/07/burke-ramsey-sues-investigator-who-accused-him-of-killing-sister/ | title=Burke Ramsey Sues Investigator Who Accused Him Of Killing Sister | author=Marcia Garcia | publisher=CBS4 New Denver |date=October 7, 2016 | access-date=October 11, 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n |url=https://www.12news.com/article/news/nation-now/jonbenet-ramseys-brother-files-defamation-suit-against-pathologist/75-329918958 \n |title=JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey's brother files defamation suit against pathologist \n |agency=Associated Press \n |publisher=12 News \n |location=Arizona \n |date=October 7, 2016 \n |access-date=September 15, 2018\n}}</ref>\n\nOn December 28, 2016, Burke Ramsey's lawyers filed an additional civil lawsuit that accused [[CBS]], the production company Critical Content LLC, and seven experts and consultants of [[United States defamation law|defamation of character]]. They sought $250 million in compensatory damages and $500 million in punitive damages.<ref>{{cite news|author=Chris Harris |url=http://people.com/crime/burke-ramsey-jonbenet-cbs-series-lawsuit/ |title=JonBenet Ramsey's Brother Burke Sues CBS for $750 Million |website=People.com |date=December 29, 2016 |access-date=March 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, a judge denied the CBS motion to dismiss, and the suit was allowed to proceed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://money.cnn.com/2018/01/06/media/jonbenet-ramsey-brother-cbs-documentary/index.html|title=Judge allows lawsuit against CBS by brother of JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey to proceed|first1=Jackie|last1=Wattles|date=2018-01-06|access-date=2018-12-26}}</ref> In January 2019, Wood announced that the lawsuit had been settled \"to the satisfaction of all parties.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-jonbenet-lawsuit-settlement-idUSKCN1OY1XP|title=JonBenet Ramsey's brother settles lawsuit with CBS: attorney|date=2019-01-04|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-01-04|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Colorado}}\n* ''[[The Case of: JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey]]''\n* ''[[Casting JonBenet]]''\n* ''[[Getting Away with Murder: The JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey Mystery]]''\n* [[Paulette Gebara Farah]]\n* [[List of murdered American children]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n<!---- sorted by year, then author's last name ---->\n* {{cite book | author=Carlton Smith | title=Death of a Little Princess: The Tragic Story of the Murder of JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey | location=New York | publisher= St. Martin's Paperbacks | year= 1997 | isbn=0312964331 }}\n* {{cite book | author= Linda Edison McLean with foreword by [[Patsy Ramsey]]| title=JonBen\u00e9t's Mother: The Tragedy and the Truth | location=Parsons, WV | publisher=McClain Print Co. | year= 1998 | isbn=0870125966}}\n* {{cite book | author=Eleanor Von Duyke and Dwight Wallington | title=A Little Girl's Dream? A JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey Story | location=Austin, TX | publisher=Windsor House | year=1998 | isbn=1881636445 }}\n* {{cite book | author=[[Cyril Wecht|Cyril H. Wecht]] and Charles Bosworth, Jr. | title=Who Killed JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey? | location=New York | publisher=Onyx Book | year=1998 | isbn=0451408713 | url=https://archive.org/details/whokilledjonbene00wech }}\n* {{cite book |author=[[Lawrence Schiller]] | title=[[Perfect Murder, Perfect Town]]: The Uncensored Story of the JonBen\u00e9t Murder and the Grand Jury's Search for the Final Truth  | location=New York |publisher=HarperCollins | year=1999 | isbn=0060191538 }}\n* {{cite book | author=Stephen Singular | title=Presumed Guilty: An Investigation into the JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey Case, the Media, and the Culture of Pornography | location=Beverly Hills, CA | publisher=New Millennium Press | year=1999 | isbn=1893224007 | url=https://archive.org/details/presumedguiltyin00sing }}\n* {{cite book | author=[[John E. Douglas]] and [[Mark Olshaker]] | chapter=The JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey Murder | title=[[The Cases That Haunt Us]] | location=New York | publisher= Scribner | year=2000 | isbn=978-0-684-84600-2 }}\n* {{cite book | author=Steve Thomas and Don Davis | title=JonBen\u00e9t: Inside the Ramsey Murder Investigation | location=New York | publisher=St. Martin's Press | year=2000 | isbn=0312253265 | url=https://archive.org/details/jonbentinsider00thom }}\n* {{ cite book | title=The Death of Innocence: JonBen\u00e9t's Parents Tell Their Story | author=[[John Bennett Ramsey|John Ramsey]] and [[Patsy Ramsey]] | location=New York | publisher=Onyx | year=2001 | isbn=0451409736 }}\n* {{cite book | title=JonBenet: The Police Files |editor=Don Gentile and David Wright | location=Boca Raton, FL | publisher=American Media | year=2003 | isbn=1932270035 }}\n* {{cite book | author=A. James Kolar | title=Foreign Faction: Who Really Kidnapped JonBen\u00e9t?&nbsp;\u2013 A Former Lead Investigator Breaks Six Years of Silence | location=Telluride, CO | publisher=Ventus Publishing | year=2012 | isbn=0984763201 }}\n* {{cite book | author=Paula Woodward | title=We Have Your Daughter: The Unsolved Murder of JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey Twenty Years Later | publisher=Prospecta Press | year=2016 | isbn=1632260778}}\n<!---- sorted by year, then author's last name ---->\n\n===Articles===\n* {{cite news | url=http://web.dailycamera.com/extra/ramsey/1997/03/03-1.html | title=Police question Boulder 'Santa,' wife | agency=Associated Press | date=March 3, 1997 | newspaper=Daily Camera }}\n* {{cite news | url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3577037/He-hellraiser-JonBenet-Ramsey-private-investigator-opens-man-responsible-6-year-old-pageant-queen-s-1996-murder-killed-just-months-crime.html | title='He was a hellraiser': JonBenet Ramsey private investigator opens up about man who may be responsible for six-year-old pageant queen's 1996 murder who killed himself just months after the crime | date=May 6, 2016 | author=Ashley Collman | newspaper=Daily Mail }}\n* {{cite journal | url=http://www.crimemagazine.com/murder-jonben%C3%A9t-ramsey | title=The Murder of JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey | publisher=Crime Magazine | author=J.J. Maloney | date=October 25, 2013 | access-date=November 19, 2014 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129041656/http://www.crimemagazine.com/murder-jonben%C3%A9t-ramsey | archive-date=November 29, 2014 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}\n* {{cite magazine | url=http://www.westword.com/2006-10-12/news/made-for-each-other/full/ | title=Made for Each Other: The Karr fiasco is over, but Michael Tracey's quest for unlikely suspects in the Ramsey case goes on and on | author=Alan Prendergast | magazine=Westword | date=October 12, 2006 }}\n* {{ cite news | url=http://web.dailycamera.com/extra/ramsey/1999/17arsid.html | title=Police sought mom's arrest | author=Matt Sebastian | newspaper=Daily Camera | date=February 17, 1999  }}\n* {{cite news | url=http://web.dailycamera.com/extra/ramsey/1998/07thomle.html | title=The Thomas resignation letter - \"We were trying to deliver a murder case with hands tied behind our backs.\" | author=Steve Thomas | date=August 6, 1998| newspaper=Daily Camera }}\n\n===Videos===\n* {{cite episode\n | title = City under siege: The news media's coverage and Boulder officials' secretive handling of the investigation into the murder of JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey\n | series =[[Nightline]]\n | network =ABC\n | air-date =January 31, 1997\n| lccn=00568713}}\n* {{cite episode\n | title = Case Closed: The Boulder Police Department's investigation into murder of JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey\n | series =[[Nightline]]\n | network =ABC\n | air-date =May 30, 1997\n| lccn=00571015}}\n* {{cite AV media | title=[[Getting Away with Murder: The JonBen\u00e9t Ramsey Mystery]] | people= Edward Lucas, director | year=2000 | publisher=Fox Broadcasting 